<HEADLINE> Thailand Eyes 9.7 million Tourist Arrivals in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Tourism Authority of Thailand (
TAT) projects that visitor arrivals to Thailand will reach some 9.
7 million in 2001, up 6.34 percent and bring about 318 billion
baht (8.15 billion U.S. dollars) revenue to the country's economy,
according to a TAT press release Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 56.7 million Thais are expected to travel
around their country, a slight increase of three percent.
</P>
<P>
Concluding a week-long marketing and development meeting
designed to further strengthen the country's position as a world-
class tourist destination, the TAT executives has decided to
promote new markets and new destinations in 2001 to sustain the
development of Thailand's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
They plan to strengthen marketing campaigns not only in
principal markets but also in supplementary markets and niche
markets.
</P>
<P>
Principal markets refer to high-spending and strong growing
markets such as Japan, China, Singapore, South Korea, Taiwan, the
United Kingdom, Germany, the United States, Scandinavia and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Supplementary markets refer to medium growing markets such as
France, Switzerland,, the Netherlands, Italy, Israel, Eastern
Europe, Indonesia and India.
</P>
<P>
In terms of niche markets, the TAT is focusing on families,
golfers, honeymooners, special interest visitors on eco-tourism,
agro-tourism and diving.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the TAT will maintain its marketing campaigns
in certain other priority markets including Malaysia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The executives of the TAT decided that the goals of Thailand's
tourism industry remain the same, that is to increase the tourism
revenue by attracting more visitors to Thailand, persuading them
to spend more and stay longer.
</P>
<P>
"We will need to be very creative in our future plans. We will
need to give visitors more reasons to come to Thailand, more
interesting tourism activities and new tour packages to attract
both first-time and repeat visitors," said Adisai Bodharamik,
newly-appointed minister to prime minister's office and TAT
chairman.
</P>
<P>
To make popular destinations less congested and further spread
distribution of tourism income, the TAT plans to promote a group
of less visited provinces by grouping them and organizing more
activities.
</P>
<P>
The TAT will also further strengthen bilateral and
international relations with neighboring countries by cooperating
in promoting the region as a single destination and organizing
more joint activities, especially overland caravans and Mekong
cruises.
</P>
<P>
The agency plans to pay much more attention to developing
sustainable tourism. "Sustainable development is TAT's priority
but tourism-related problems need to be addressed by both public
and private organizations," Adisai said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of marketing strategies and campaigns, the TAT will
maintain the "Amazing Thailand" slogan.
</P>
<P>
TAT governor Pradech Phayakvichien said the TAT would continue
to work with related public and private agencies as well as local
communities to help them maximize tourism earnings.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, international tourist arrivals to Thailand totaled 8.
58 million, up 10.5 percent over 1998, generating 253 billion baht
(seven billion dollars) earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
