<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Combat AIDS With More Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
undertake more preventive measures including awareness campaign,
needle exchange and condom promotion to fight against deadly
disease AIDS, a senior official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Health and Family Welfare Minister Sheikh Fazlul Karim Selim
announced the government plan at a workshop which concluded here
Monday, suggesting to strengthen preventive measures as the
scourge alarmed the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"HIV and AIDS became a matter of global concern. Epidemiology
of the disease has been well documented since 1980," the minister
said when addressing as the chief guest at the closing ceremony of
the two-day workshop on "HIV Surveillance: Issues and Implications,
" which was jointly organized by the government of Bangladesh and
United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony was organized for dissemination of the
results of the second round of the National Sentinel Surveillance
for HIV, which was conducted from August 1999 to May 2000,
covering groups exhibiting high-risk behavior such as sex workers,
injecting drug users, homosexuals, and rickshaw-pullers.
</P>
<P>
The surveillance results showed that the "prevalence of
syphilis, although lower, was still high in all groups surveyed (
18.4 percent) and was the highest in the female sex worker groups
as was the case last year."
</P>
<P>
HIV prevalence rates were unchanged compared to the 1st round (
1996-1999) and the rates ranged from 0 to 0.3 percent. "Bangladesh
is lucky that the HIV prevalence rate is still low. However, risk
behavior and high syphilis rates indicate the potential for rapid
spread," the conference noted.
</P>
<P>
The meeting emphasized the need for strong political commitment
at all levels, starting with the highest but extending down to the
community leadership and continued vigilance and monitoring of the
epidemic through HIV and Risk Behavior Surveillance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
