<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's BDR Chief Stresses Border Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Director General of Bangladesh Rifles
(BDR) Major General A. L. M. Fazlur Rahman said it is necessary to
set up BDR camps on every 20 kilometers of the unprotected
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) border and at least four heliports in
the region, the United News of Bangladesh reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said a total of 479 kilometers of border in Chittagong
Hill Tracts in the eastern part of the country remains unprotected.
The government has withdrawn all BDR and Army camps from 379 km
border with India and 100 km border with Myanmar in Chittagong
Hill Tracts, he added.
</P>
<P>
The BDR Chief expressed concern that armed rebels and
international drug traffickers might intrude into the deep jungles
of CHT area through the unprotected borders and set up camps there.
</P>
<P>
In Rahman's view, curbing cross border smuggling by task force
is not possible, because it is impossible to bring together
customs officials, magistrate and police for taking on-the-spot
decision against the smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The strength of BDR should be raised to at least 70,000 to man
the borders, he suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
