<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, EU to Strive to Win Freedom for Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany and the European Union (EU)
both said Monday that they will do everything to win freedom for
the 20 Western and Asian hostages who have been held by Philippine
Islamic extremists for over two months.
</P>
<P>
"We want to guarantee the lives and security of the hostages
and to get them free," said visiting EU representative for common
foreign and security policy Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
Solana made this remark during a meeting with German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer. He added that the EU will continue its
efforts, but now there are no initiatives now.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Fischer said he would not make comment on the
fate of German reporter Andreas Lorenz, who was kidnapped Sunday
while seeking to contact the hostage-takers.
</P>
<P>
"This is a new situation. I don't want to assess it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two also discussed the development of European security
and defense policy and reached agreement on many issues, according
to Fischer.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Extremist group leader Abu Sayyaf is still
holding captive three Germans, two French, two Finns, two South
Africans, one Lebanese, eight other Malaysians and two Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were kidnapped on April 23 from the diving resort
of Sipadan in neighboring Malaysia and taken to Jolo island in the
southern Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
