<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Ugandan Movement's Win Attributed to Positive Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Ding Qilin and Wang Shangzhi
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Ugandan National
Resistance Movement won the overwhelming majority of votes cast in
the June 29 referendum, which has determined that Uganda will
continuously adopt the present Movement System instead of
Multi-party System as the nation's political system.
</P>
<P>
In the national referendum, the Movement System attracted 4.322
million votes, accounting for 90.7 percent, while the Multi-party
gained 442,823 votes, registering at 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the economic progress achieved in the east
African country in the past 14 years has played a pivotal role in
the Movement's landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
Soon after it came into power, the Movement administration
launched reforms in various sectors, particularly in economic and
public sectors.
</P>
<P>
Under the Movement leadership, Uganda witnessed an average GDP
growth of 6 percent, with the highest registered at 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the 1999-2000 fiscal year, the agriculture sector gained 3
percent growth despite severe droughts and the industrial
production rose by 6.2 percent, while manufacturing, construction,
utilities and transport shot up by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Uganda has seen dramatic improvement of its education
and health.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the Universal Primary Education program
brought school enrolments from 2.5 million to 6.5 million pupils.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of people infected by HIV/AIDS dropped
from 30 percent of the country's total population in 1987 to the
present 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Movement Political System is defined as broad-based, inclusive
and non- partisan, which features the participatory democracy,
transparency, accessibility to all positions of leadership by all
citizens, and individual merit as a basis for election to
political offices. Before the Movement gained power in 1986,
the local government structure under the multi-party system was
made up of district councils, which were appointed by the minister
responsible for Local Government, and the same minister also had
the power to fire them.
</P>
<P>
Under the Movement government, district councils are made up of
elected councilors with differing shades of political opinions.
</P>
<P>
Federalists, Multi-partyists, Movementists, Protestants,
Muslims and Catholics could all become council members. The
chairmen of the district councils are directly elected by secret
ballot, and the councilors and chairmen of the sub-counties under
the districts are also directly elected through universal
suffrage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in all the elections candidates are elected on their
 individual merit. Although they are not sponsored by parties,
they state their political conviction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Servants' Strike Spreading in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian trade union leaders said
Monday that the public sector strike that began last month in
Lagos is spreading to other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Nigerian Labor Congress (NLC) , the
country's largest trade union, said that civil servants in about
10 of Nigeria's 36 states are either on strike or are about to
join the strike.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants in Lagos and the oil-producing states of the
south are demanding a monthly minimum wage equivalent to about
7,500 naira (about 75 U.S. dollars). Those in other states are
demanding about 6,500 naira.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, the strike is already in its second week. Public
hospitals and schools have been badly affected, while huge piles
of uncollected rubbish accumulating on many street corners.
</P>
<P>
This follows an earlier strike last month over petrol prices,
which brought much of the country to a standstill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
