<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Strategic Option for Jordan: King Abdullah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
stressed on Tuesday that peace remains a strategic option for
Jordan, and the kingdom will continue its efforts to promote the
Arab-Israeli peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a written interview with Xinhua, King Abdullah said currently
the peace process is at a delicate stage, and Jordan has been and
will be in persistent touches with parties concerned to revive and
push forward peace talks on all fronts, including the Palestinian
and Syrian tracks.
</P>
<P>
The monarch said he hoped progress could soon be made on the
suspended Syrian-Israeli peace talks, and he felt, through talks
with Syrian leader Bashar al-Assad earlier this year, that Syria
was keen to reach peace by means of recovering all lands occupied
by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks broke off in January after Israel
rejected a Syrian demand to give back in full the strategic Golan
Heights which Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks between Israel and the Palestinians have
entered the final stage, and the Palestinians are determined to
restore their legitimate rights, including the establishment of an
independent state on their own soil, Abdullah said in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that only by achieving peace can peoples in the
region look forward to security and stability, and to devoting all
their attention to building up a brighter future and a better life
for the coming generations.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, the second
Arab country following Egypt to reach such a peace deal with the
Jewish state. Since then, Jordan has been a major peace broker
between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah told Xinhua he believed that after achieving peace in
the region, there would be vast potential for economic cooperation
between Israel and its former Arab foes, and Arab countries will be
able to concentrate on improving their economies, creating more
jobs, alleviating poverty and curbing unemployment rates.
</P>
<P>
Apart from official ties, people to people contacts should also
be strengthened between Israel and Arab countries, and a
comprehensive social and economic development would be conducive in
return to peace and stability in the region, the king said.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic front, King Abdullah said his top priority was
to shoulder the unfulfilled tasks of his late father King Hussein
Ibn Talal to develop national economy and to improve the economic
performance of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah acceded to the throne after Hussein who ruled Jordan
for nearly half a century died of cancer in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We must double our efforts to improve the economy and the
people's living standards to meet the development trend in a world
which is under enormous changes," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
During his 15-month reign, Abdullah has ordered amendments to
laws and regulations to improve the kingdom's investment conditions
both for domestic and foreign investors, and rendered it a top
priority for his government to develop the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been developing cooperative relations with
international organizations and friendly countries, and has signed
a series of economic deals with other countries after it entered
the World Trade Organization (WTO) in late 1999, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said currently his kingdom is actively negotiating a
free trade agreement with the United States to attract more foreign
investments and to create more jobs for Jordanian citizens.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan has also improved its ties with Syria and the
Gulf states, and he believed in closer economic cooperation between
Jordan and Syria after Bashar came to power.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old monarch has established a close personal
relationship with Bashar, son of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
who died of a heart attack last month.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's ties with Syria soured after Jordan signed the peace
treaty with Israel in 1994 as Assad had stood against any
unilateral Arab action to reach peace with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's relations with Gulf states were also adversely affected
during the 1990 Gulf crisis as Jordan was seen to be standing with
Iraq after Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
