<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Should Prepare Law on Genetics: Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish parliament should set up
a
commission promoting genetic studies and preparing laws on genetics
in order to closely follow the latest developments of the genetic
studies in the world, one Turkish professor proposed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ali Sazi, professor of Kocaeli University Medical Faculty and
head of the Micro-Biology department, said that many scientists
have told the press about the deciphering of the DNA, but some
of these claims were exaggerated, Anatolia news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Scientists in several countries recently announced that they
have deciphered 97 percent of sequences of human genomes.
</P>
<P>
Sazi warned that some scientists are misleading public,
interpreting the DNA's deciphering as a "remedy for death".
</P>
<P>
Death is inevitable, Sazi said, adding that medical inventions
can only help people live longer.
</P>
<P>
He said that the three percent of the DNA which has not yet been
deciphered, will soon be revealed.
</P>
<P>
The professor said that Turkey has "valuable" experts in genetic
engineering, but that they have not received enough financial
support in their studies.
</P>
<P>
He said that "medical studies are progressing very slowly in our
country where no long-term plans are being made like in Europe or
the United States."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Turkish government to integrate with the world in
the
genetic studies, and benefit from the medical developments.
</P>
<P>
A genetic commission should be formed in the Parliament and a
law on genetics should be prepared. If these measures are realized,
medical researches will be strengthened and universities will be
given financial assistance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sazi said that the commission will monitor and avoid some wrong
implementations regarding people's genetic structure in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
