<HEADLINE> Turkey Eyes for Third Tranche of Stand-by Loans with IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is eyeing for the 300 million
U.S. dollars third tranche of a 4-billion-dollar stand-by loan that
was endorsed by the IMF at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The managing directors of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
will review a supplementary letter of intent from Turkey on
Thursday. Upon approval of the letter, the IMF is expected to
release the third tranche.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year loan package, Turkey pledged to reduce its
chronic inflation and budget deficits, undertake a comprehensive
privatization program and reform agriculture, Turkish Daily News
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government promised to reduce inflation to 20 percent in
2000, 10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. The annual
inflation rate stood at 58.6 percent in June this year, down from
68.9 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The IMF approval is expected to further ease Turkey's
international borrowing. The Treasury plans to launch a euro-
dominated bond issue this month.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the Treasury's external borrowing through bond
issuance has totaled 5.1 billion dollars, compared to a full-year
target of 6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury has programed to undertake another 1.4 billion
dollars in external borrowing in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
IMF Turkish desk chief Carlo Cottarelli is scheduled to arrive
in Turkey for the third stand-by review of the disinflation program
after August 25.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by IMF Turkish desk experts said the country
has met until now IMF's performance criteria and carried out its
commitments without resorting to populist policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
