<HEADLINE> 52 Canadian Hunters Airlifted to Safety from Arctic Floe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- As many as 52 hunters have been
airlifted to safety from a broken Arctic ice floe, Canada's
northern Nunavut government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The hunters from Arctic Bay were likely going after narwhal or
seal when they found themselves drifting away on a giant pan of
ice, that was more than 25 kilometers long and wide, and nearly a
meter thick.
</P>
<P>
A helicopter was immediately sent out to airlift five or six
people at a time into nearby Cape Crawford until all the trapped
hunters were taken out of the drifting mass of ice.
</P>
<P>
Mike Ferris, deputy minister in charge of the local emergency
services, said that the hunters were being flown home to Arctic
Bay on a Twin Otter ferry service after the incidence of "an
annual occurrence." 
</P>
