<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- In the first five months of this
year, exports of Chilean wines reached 219.52 million U.S. dollars,
increasing by 24.78 percent compared with 1999's same period.
</P>
<P>
According to Chilean firm CHILEVID dedicated to wine producing
and exporting, such value corresponded to an export volume of 97.
99 million liters. But the average price went down in the same
period in question, from 2.25 to 2.24 dollars a liter.
</P>
<P>
The same source said this rise of almost a quarter of value
shows the constant increase of sending the country's wines abroad
during the whole length of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
This tendency was reversed only in 1999, when due to the fall
of purchases from Japan the figure went below that of 1998,
explained CHILEVID General Manager Rodrigo Alvarado.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the 1990s, Chile only exported wines for a
value of 38 million dollars a year. 
