<HEADLINE> Panama Criticizes EU's Banana Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has no
intention to change preferential banana treatment for its old
colonies, which prejudiced Latin America's banana exports, a
Panamanian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Panama's Vice Foreign Trade Minister Roberto Henriquez said the
European bloc is preparing itself to continue discriminating
policies against Latin American exporters.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the EU doesn't want to adapt itself to
World Trade Organization (WTO) clauses, provoking a loss for over
12 million U.S. dollars in year 2000's first three-month period
for Panama.
</P>
<P>
Henriquez estimated these figures projected to a year will give
as a result 50 million dollars in losses in banana production,
which has affected mainly its Atlantic sector land, where the
largest part of the county's banana is grown.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the EU established a yearly quota to its market for an
amount of just 700,000 metric tons of boxes of banana at a Latin
American standard, which also includes Ecuador, a country that
individually can produce over 4 million metric tons.
</P>
<P>
This discriminating policy stops exporters in the field such as
Honduras, Guatemala, Nicaragua, Ecuador, Colombia, and Costa Rica
from placing more production on the European market, where
countries of Africa and the Caribbean gain preference as EU ex-
colonies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
