<HEADLINE> Four More Arrested in Egypt for Involvement in Case Against American Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Four more people have been arrested in
Egypt for the case against an Egyptian-American sociology professor
at American University in Cairo, bringing to 10 the number of the
detained in the case, the prosecutor's office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The four people who work for the Ibn Khaldoun Center for
Development Studies were arrested Monday evening after four of
their colleagues were arrested earlier in the day, reported Egypt's
Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The professor, Saad Eddin Ibrahim, who is also the center's
director, was arrested Saturday on charges including receiving
funds from abroad without obtaining prior permission from the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The eight detained on Monday were being questioned about their
involvement in the case of fraudulent electoral cards found on the
center's premises, the prosecutor's office added.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the prosecutor's office specifically accused Ibrahim
of having instructed researchers at the center to register
fictitious names of voters on the cards and paid each one 300
Egyptian pounds (around 90 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim then received 50,000 pounds (14,500 dollars) from the
European Union as part of a program sponsored by the 15-nation
European bloc to educate citizens about their civic rights, the
office said.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim faces 15 years in prison if found guilty of the charges,
which include drafting reports on the internal situation in Egypt,
Morocco, Tunisia and other Arab countries in exchange for money
from abroad. The reports would tarnish Egypt's image and undermine
its stability, security prosecutors said. 
</P>
