<HEADLINE> Iraq Opposes Saudi Move to Increase Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq opposed the announcement made
by Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, which will weaken the
role of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC), an official of the Iraqi oil ministry said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq deemed the current oil price at the international market
as "proper and acceptable", the official said.
</P>
<P>
The increase of oil production by Saudi Arabia will hurt the
interests of the OPEC countries, as the oil price will surely drop,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia made the decision to increase oil output under the
pressure of the United States, who has long been calling for the
OPEC to lift oil output, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has announced to increase oil output by 500,000
barrels per day (bpd) to alleviate the surge of oil price, which
runs as high as 30.10 U.S. dollars recently.
</P>
<P>
OPEC officials have expressed readiness to increase oil output
to stablize the international oil market.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long demanded the OPEC not to loose its reins in oil
output to quench the attempts of the U.S., the biggest oil
consumer, to raise oil output.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid has said that
Iraq plans to increase its oil production to about 3.3 million bpd
by the end of the year, the level before the U.N. sanctions started
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil production in May reached 3.1 million bpd, compared
with 2.63 million bpd in April and 2.16 million bpd in March.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil output are monitored by the U.N. not by the OPEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
