<HEADLINE> Northern Cyprus Protested for Building New Check Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The government of Cyprus Tuesday
sent a letter to the United Nations outlining its position on
measures the Turkish Cypriot side has taken to curtail the movement
of the U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
In the letter, it demanded the situation near the village of
Strovilia on the southern eastern part of Cyprus, where the Turkish
troops built a new check point, will be reversed to its original
agreed status.
</P>
<P>
The letter was delivered Tuesday by Permanent Secretary of
Cyprus' Foreign Ministry Michalis Attalides to Zbigniew Wlosowicz,
the U.N. special representative in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Turkish military constructed a new check point
in Strovilia, violating the status quo in the area with a view to
restricting the movement of UNFICYP soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash announced among
other measures the closure of all but one point of entry into
northern Cyprus by the U.N. peacekeepers in retaliation for the U.
N. decision to renew their mandate without asking for its approval.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, Wlosowicz said he will study
the Cyprus government's letter carefully.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. has challenged the construction of the new
check point, adding he has protested against in his letter to
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no other change along the confrontation line,
apart from the situation created by the new check point at
Strovilia.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the U.N. peacekeepers have maintained the 180-
kilometre-long ceasefire line dividing the two communities. 
</P>
