<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Attacks U.N. for Harming Geneva Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
on Tuesday lashed out at the United Nations for its decision to
extend the mandate of the U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus
(UNFICYP) without consulting the Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
While speaking to reporters during a stopover at Ataturk Airport
of Istanbul on his way to Geneva for the third round of "proximity
talks" on Cyprus, Denktash described the U.N. move as a shadow cast
on the talks at the beginning, Anatolia News Agency reported
</P>
<P>
"The (U.N.) Security Council acted unfairly against us," he
said. "They encouraged Greek Cypriots by saying that they were the
government of whole Cyprus and that the U.N. soldiers can perform
on Cyprus with their consent only."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council decided on June 15 to renew the
mandate of the UNFICYP for another term of six months with the
consent of the government of Cyprus, without the approval of the
Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Angered by the move, the Turkish Cypriot side, for the first
time since 1964, decided last week to impose a series of
restrictions on the U.N. force, including limiting its travel and
revoking its free electricity and water.
</P>
<P>
Denktash warned the measures taken against the UNFICYP are just
the beginning, and that if the U.N. insists on not acknowledging
the existence of the "Turkish Cypriot state" in northern Cyrus,
further and tougher measures will follow.
</P>
<P>
It was reported the measures, which came only days before the U.
N.-brokered "proximity talks" are scheduled to start on July 5 in
Geneva, have placed the Turkish Cypriot side on a collision course
with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus has been split into
the Turkish and Greek Cypriot communities since 1974 following a
Turkish invasion in the wake of a short-lived coup by supporters of
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored reunification talks are deadlocked due to the
insistence of the Turkish side on the recognition of the breakaway
entity and the rejection of U.N. Security Council resolutions on a
solution to the Cyprus issue on the basis of a bi-zonal and bi-
communal federation.
</P>
<P>
In response to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's appeal, Greek
Cypriot leader Glafcos Clerides and Denktash went for two rounds
of "proximity talks" in New York late last year and in Geneva
earlier this year. No tangible results were reported, but the two
sides agreed for more talks.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the prospect of the renewed Geneva talks, Denktash
said, "We are going there with good will. We will not close the
compromise doors if they are open. It should be an agreement that
protects our rights, prevents the repetition of things that
happened to us, and that protects the rights of Turkey on Cyprus,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have prepared its contents. A confederal solution is the
name of this. We are presenting the way for compromise if they want
compromise. We will continue to do this." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
