<HEADLINE> France Proposes Measures Against Illegal Immigration in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- France presented Tuesday to the
European Parliament some proposals on the measures to be taken by
the European Union (EU) against illegal immigration in Europe.
</P>
<P>
French State Secretary of Overseas Territories Jean-Jacques
Queyranne, who presented the proposals in Strasbourg, said that
the deteriorating problem of illegal immigration is caused by a
growing number of networks which are bringing illegal immigrants
to Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
He accused mafias in Russia, Turkey and Albania of
orchestrating on the frontline illegal immigration in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in a fight against immigration, but a fight against
criminals," he said.
</P>
<P>
The French proposals include a better harmonization of the laws
of the 15 EU countries in the fields of providing asylum, banning
illegal immigrants from their territories, and punishing the
people who transport or help illegal immigrants to enter EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
Those who transport illegal immigrants will be fined at least 2,
000 euros (1,880 U.S. dollars) and be forced to pay for the return
fees of the immigrants, according to the French proposal.
</P>
<P>
France also called for support to the policy of "co-development
" which is aimed at discouraging illegal immigration by providing
economic aid to the home countries of illegal immigrants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: U.N. Promotes Information Technology  (by Ding Baozhong) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of the main topics of the conference, an annual event of
the U.N. Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) but with peculiar
interest this year, is how to take measures to overcome the lag in
IT use in the less developed countries, according to the ECOSOC.
</P>
<P>
A document is expected to be adopted at the three-day gathering
to endorse a global action plan involving the U.N., international
agencies, countries and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Delegates will see how developing countries are determined to
catch up with the global impetus to promote IT in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
President Alpha Oumar Konare of Mali, one of the world's 48
less developed countries, is to address the ECOSOC Thursday. He
has placed governmental operations on line and is launching a
program to link 700 communes digitally in his country.
</P>
<P>
Internationally, only in the last year or two has the severity
of the consequences of the digital gap become clear, a U.N. panel
of experts has found.
</P>
<P>
Electronic commerce is inexorably bringing individuals, firms
and countries closer together, but countries without advanced
capabilities are being pushed out of the loop.
</P>
<P>
Less than 5 percent of the world's population accounts for the
1.5 billion web pages in existence, with almost 2 million more
appearing on the Internet every day, and for e-commerce exchanges
on track to reach 7 trillion U.S. dollars in 2004, the panel said
in a report to be put before delegates.
</P>
<P>
"E-commerce is rapidly becoming a trade barrier for those who
are not connected" and countries unable to stay abreast of the IT
revolution face the fate of being "completely bypassed," the
experts warned.
</P>
<P>
The international community needs to be galvanized to address
the IT emergency in a coordinated rather than piece-meal fashion,
said the ECOSOC president, Ambassador Makarim Wibisono of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has increasingly paid attention to its
coordinator role in spreading IT, with Secretary-General Kofi
Annan spearheading the creation of an IT task force to bring
together international agencies, private industry and foundations
to facilitate the expansion of IT markets in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the impact of ECOSOC initiatives depends on the
response by the U.N. Millennium Assembly scheduled for September,
individual governments, major economies of the Group of Seven and
the Bretton Woods institutions and other international
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan to Beef Up Efforts Against Evil Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUSHANBE, Tajikistan, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China and Kazakhstan
agreed here Tuesday to strengthen their coordination in fighting
against separatism, terrorism and extremism and in warding off
external attempts sabotaging peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two countries came to the agreement during a meeting
between President Jiang Zemin and Kazakhstan President Nursultan
Nazarbayev, who are here to attend the fifth summit of the "
Shanghai Five" nations to be held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The "Shanghai Five" summit brings together heads of state from
China, Tajikistan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan to discuss
regional and international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Jiang said he hopes that China and
Kazakhstan will come up with more effective measures in their
concerted efforts against separatism, terrorism and extremism, and
against external forces trying to sabotage peace and stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev said his country will actively coordinate and
cooperate with China in such efforts.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Nazarbayev that Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao
will visit Kazakhstan soon for furthering the high-level contacts
between the two countries. Nazarbayev expressed welcome to Hu's
visit.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev also said that Kazakhstan firmly supports the one-
China principle and wishes China greater achievements in the cause
of national unification.
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived here Monday on a two-day state visit to
Tajikistan, the first ever by a Chinese head of state, before the
"Shanghai Five" summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
