<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World AIDS Conference Expected to Draw 11,000 Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The 13th World AIDS
Conference, the first to be hosted in the African continent, is
expected to draw more than 11,000 delegates from across the world,
said conference organizer Karen Bennett on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The week-long conference will be opened by South African
President Thabo Mbeki in Durban on July 9, and some 20 million
people are expected to witness the official opening on television
on the day as the event is broadcast live to 70 countries in the
world, Bennet said.
</P>
<P>
She said that a large number of delegates and journalists will
come from developing countries, where the effect of HIV/AIDS is
most keenly felt.
</P>
<P>
About 178 countries will be represented at the conference,
which will focus on breaking the silence over the disease which
has already killed millions, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also deal with such issues as equal access
to treatment for AIDS sufferers, caring for people with AIDS,
children living with AIDS, human rights, vaccine development and
the impact of the disease on the developing world.
</P>
<P>
According to Bennett, the accommodation areas were divided into
four zones and four buses will serve each zone daily and ferry
delegates to and from the International Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
A number of South African cabinet ministers and provincial
health officials will attend the conference and former South
African president Nelson Mandela will announce the closing on July
14, she said.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the world's HIV/AIDS population live in Africa,
and South Africa, where the number of HIV infected people has
rocketed since the early 1990s, is home to an estimated 4.2
million HIV/AIDS sufferers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
