<HEADLINE> S. African Military Concerned About Safety of Peacekeepers in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The South African military is
concerned about the safety of some of its technical teams to be
deployed in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the
parliamentary portfolio committee on defense said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
South African National Defense Force members involved in
peacekeeping operations in the DRC, particularly in the capital
Kinshasa, would not be adequately protected, said director of
joint operations Brigadier-General Jan Lusse.
</P>
<P>
Indications are that the teams to be deployed at four sectoral
headquarters in the DRC would be adequately protected but those
doing duty in Kinshasa would be exposed to ongoing volatility in
the area, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He told the committee in Pretoria that the issue should be
reconsidered and the postponement of the deployment has made it
possible to review this matter.
</P>
<P>
Committee members also expressed concern about the matter,
saying more intelligence is needed on the issue.
</P>
<P>
South Africans should be dispatched to the DRC with the good
wishes of the committee, but this would not be possible unless the
committee has sufficient information on operational conditions in
the DRC, said committee chairwoman Thandi Modise.
</P>
<P>
On his side, African National Congress member of parliament
Thabang Makwetla proposed that the committee arrange another
meeting to enquire into the issue of intelligence.
</P>
<P>
It is also necessary to dig deeper into the financial
implications of the DRC mission, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that none of the 165 specialized South African
peacekeepers to be deployed to the DRC will carry weapons with
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
