<HEADLINE> FAO Helps Rehabilitate Angolan Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has got 1.3
million U. S. dollars aid from the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) to help rehabilitate agricultural production in
the country, the official news agency Angop reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This project, as part of the FAO assistance to the Angolan
government, will improve the coordination of the emergency
agricultural programs and the supply of farming instruments to
2,400 peasant families.
</P>
<P>
The project is also aimed to reinforce the operational and
technical capacity of the services in the central highland
provinces supported by Angolan Agriculture Ministry as well as to
improve the efficiency of the seeds distributors in the provinces
and the quality of the seeds.
</P>
<P>
The central areas are considered as the traditional base of
Angola's agricultural production, with fertile soil and ample
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
The program, approved late June in Rome, was funded by the
Italian government, following the FAO's consolidated appeal last
year in favour of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Four other projects, financed by France, Italy and Belgium and
estimated at 697,700 dollars, were approved in February this year
and are in progress in the provinces of Bengo, Huila and Huambo.
</P>
</TEXT>
