<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's New Parliament Urged to Restart Constitutional Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The opposition National
Constitutional Assembly (NCA) of Zimbabwe Tuesday called on the
new parliament to immediately pass a resolution to restart the
constitutional review process.
</P>
<P>
NCA spokesman Brian Kagoro told reporters that no single entity
or group should be allowed to dominate the review process.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe is bigger than political parties," he said, stressing
that " the new constitution must reflect the interests of a
broader spectrum of people in the country."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabweans must write their own constitution without fear or
intimidation by one group or party, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the new parliament to promulgate a law to set up an
inclusive legal framework for constitutional review.
</P>
<P>
The new parliament, he said, should make an undertaking not to
amend the constitution without consulting the people of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
A constitution draft compiled by the government was voted down
in a referendum in February this year. 
</P>
