<HEADLINE> No Pressure For Mugabe to Go: Zimbabwean Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) Tuesday
dismissed allegations that the party's supreme body and newly
elected legislators were pressuring President Robert Mugabe to
relinquish the party's leadership within six months.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Administration of ZANU-PF Didymus Mutasa told the
Zimbabwe News Agency that the party's Political Bureau never
discussed the matter at its meetings on Wednesday and Friday last
week.
</P>
<P>
The need for Mugabe to give up the party leadership to allow
for the election of a new leader is never an issue for discussion,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He accused independent media organizations of being the ones
trying to destroy the ruling party by making such allegations.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, several newly elected legislators
and provincial heads are pressuring Mugabe to go so that the party
can be rejuvenated in preparation for the 2002 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
ZANU-PF won the recent parliamentary election by a narrow
margin. It secured only 62 of the 120 elected seats while the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change gained 57. The other
seat went to Zimbabwe African National Union-Ndonga.
</P>
<P>
In the election, the ruling party lost almost all of the urban
constituencies. 
</P>
