<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White Farmers Concern Over Post Election Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Commercial Farmers Union (CFU)
of Zimbabwe Tuesday said post-election violence needs to be
addressed immediately as the agricultural sector has now been
affected to an extent that it may fail to recover.
</P>
<P>
CFU Deputy Director Jerry Grant said fresh farm invasions
erupted at some farms in various provinces and the situation had
reached a desperate point.
</P>
<P>
Black war veterans have occupied about 1,500 white farms since
February this year to pressure the government to speed up the land
reform.
</P>
<P>
Grant said the unfortunate thing was that the war veterans were
causing problems on farms that were not even among 804 gazetted on
June 2 for acquisition.
</P>
<P>
"We want to get back to business, but there can be no progress
on this important issue until the rule of law is re-introduced and
the unlawful occupants of the farms are removed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy director said the impact of these disturbances on
farms would be felt next year as most farmers had failed to
continue with their usual business because they could not work
under an environment of lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
CFU President Tim Henwood said in a statement that "farmers are
unable to plan ahead and are not investing in their farms as
confidence has evaporated."
</P>
<P>
"The downstream effect on the industry and other sectors of the
economy are now being felt and worse is still to come," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
