<HEADLINE> Erekat: Door of Palestinian-Israeli Peace Still Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians have not closed the
door of its peace talks with Israel and are ready to further push
forward the process, Saeb Erekat, Palestinian chief negotiator for
interim talks said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Erekat's remarks came in response to the remarks made by Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy who considered the Palestinian decision
to declare the Palestinian statehood on September 13 as the
Palestinian
withdrawal from the peace process.
</P>
<P>
After the conclusion of the two-day meeting of Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO) Central Council in Gaza on Monday,
the council decided to declare the Palestinian statehood on
September 13.
</P>
<P>
Levy made it certain after the meetings of the Israeli
parliamentary foreign and security committees on Tuesday afternoon
that the Israeli government will not say yes to the Palestinian
serious and extremist demands.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Minister of Justice Yossi Beilin said Tuesday morning
that should the Palestinian statehood be declared unilaterally, it
would not be recognized by Israel.
</P>
<P>
If the world countries recognize the Palestinian statehood, it
will remain just ink on paper as Israel will not allow the
Palestinians to run their daily affairs independently, Beilin
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
