<HEADLINE> Manila Says Hostage Negotiations Entering Delicate Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that negotiations for the release of the 20 remaining
hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf in Jolo island in Sulu province
are now entering a "delicate stage."
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora made this assessment in a
radio interview even as he declined the reported offers by local
leaders to help in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"It is good that some people are offering to help. But talks
are entering a delicate stage, and things may only get complicated.
We hope they put their offers on hold. When the time comes that we
would need their help, we hope their offers still stand," Zamora
said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government continues to negotiate with the Abu
Sayyaf for the release of the 20 hostages following the release of
a Malaysian hostage last month. They were abducted from Malaysia
on April 23 and later taken to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Reports indicated that a sultan in Sulu had offered to help in
the negotiating efforts, but the Philippine government declined
the offer for now.
</P>
<P>
Zamora also expressed the hope that a group of "prayer warriors,
" led by Jesus Miracle Crusade evangelist Wilde Almeda, will
return to Manila soon.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Almeda and 12 other members of the Jesus Miracle
Crusade entered the Abu Sayyaf's lair in Talipao town last
Saturday to pray over the 20 mostly foreign hostages.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said Almeda and his group have sent word making it clear
that they were not being held hostage by the Abu Sayyaf, in
contradiction with reports that Abu Sayyaf gunmen are demanding 10
million pesos (250,000 U.S. dollars) for their release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Radulan Sahiron, one of the six Abu Sayyaf
commanders, said Tuesday that he has custody of German journalist
Andreas Lorenz who is covering the hostage crisis in Sulu area.
Police said Lorenz was abducted by a group of gunmen last Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
