<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Penguins Released into Sea in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- By noon on Tuesday some 7,300
penguins have been transported across the country and released
into the sea at Cape Recife near Port Elizabeth to escape their
oil polluted island homes off Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
There have only been eight fatalities among the penguins
transported 800 kilometers by truck from Cape Town to Port
Elizabeth, said Harry Watts, chief marine and coastal conservation
inspector in Port Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
He said more eggs had been found in the boxes in which the
birds were contained for the trip.
</P>
<P>
"The whole operation is going very well," he said, noting that
"the assistance from the public and the South African National
Defense Force and Cape Nature Conservation has been fantastic."
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the moment the trucks arrived in
Port Elizabeth, the priority was to get the birds into the sea as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"They must not stay in the truck any longer than necessary and
must be taken to the sea immediately," he said, adding that "in
this respect the army has been very helpful."
</P>
<P>
Army personnel and conservation staff were being used to free
the penguins on the beach, after which the boxes would be trucked
back to Cape Town for use again.
</P>
<P>
The object of the cross-country exercise is to make the
penguins swim back to their home on Dassen and Robben islands, so
giving workers a chance to clean tons of oil spilled from a
carrier which sank off the Cape West coast on June 23.
</P>
<P>
Only birds not dirtied by the oil are being sent to Port
Elizabeth. The soiled birds have been cleaned at the
rehabilitation centres in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Pollution control officials were hoping for strong winds which
would either blow the oil slicks out to sea or onto the beaches,
where it could be cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Fund for Animal Welfare, the oil
slick covered a combined area of about 51 square kilometers in
Table Bay in Cape Town on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
