<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strikes Cause Loss of 1 Million Working Days in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- About 1 million working days
have been lost due to strikes by the end of June this year in
South Africa, said industrial relations consultancy Andrew Levy
and Associates on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Strikes arising from wage negotiations were up from last year's
13.8 percent to 14.7 percent, the agency said in a research
report, noting that most strikes over the past six months were in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
These included an 11-day illegal strike at the Volkswagen
factory in Uitenhage in the Eastern Cape in January, and a one-day
strike by about 55, 000 truck drivers in February during a wage
negotiation deadlock between the Road Freight Employers'
Association and six unions.
</P>
<P>
The report projected that more strike actions are expected
during the third quarter of the year when the bulk of wage
negotiations get under way.
</P>
<P>
However, some big industrial sectors such as car manufacturers
and the mining and metal industries already had long-term
agreements in place which would help reduce the number of strikes,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
