<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Celebrates 6th Liberation Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan community Tuesday
celebrated the the country's 6th Liberation anniversary to mark
the achievements so far made by the government in national unity,
Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Rwandans should be proud of what has so far been achieved,"
said Patrick Mazimhaka, a special envoy to the Rwandan President.
</P>
<P>
He said "efforts have been made to reconstruct the country in
social, economic and political spheres."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Secretary General of the Rwanda Patriotic Front
(RPF) Charles Muligande noted that the new government has
inherited serious problems from the old regime, including total
destruction of all development activities and thousands of
Rwandans displaced internally and externally.
</P>
<P>
Over 3 million Rwandan refugees were repatriated and more than
30,000 orphans reintegrated in the past three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The government also put in extra effort in developing human
resources," he added.
</P>
<P>
Good governance is now prevailing in Rwandan society and the
decentralization process is underway to facilitate transparency
and accountability.
</P>
<P>
However, Rwandans still have a long way to go for total
liberation to be achieved. There is need to fight ignorance,
poverty and AIDS that hinder development.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda was liberated in 1994, after a genocide that had
devastated the entire country and claimed over 1 million Rwandans.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
