<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Hits Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A heat wave is hitting Greece
raising temperatures sharply up to as high as 40 degrees Celsius
in many parts of the country, compared with the record high close
to 36 degrees reported in the first week of July.
</P>
<P>
The heat, beginning Sunday, has brought one of the hottest
summers to Greece over recent years, and is expected to intensify
within this week and peak on Wednesday with temperatures possibly
topping 42 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
As the government is trying to tackle natural disasters,
hospitals, health centers and ambulance services have made
themselves ready for emergencies while state and municipal air-
conditioned sports grounds and halls have been made available to
heat sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The country's fire brigades, while on high alert, have stepped
up patrols of the forests surrounding the capital of Athens, and
if necessary, will be backed by the Greek Air Force fire-fighting
planes.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Health Ministry has advised people, especially the
young and the elderly, to take steps to protect themselves from
the heat wave. The Athens city hall has set up a medical help-line
for citizens.
</P>
<P>
Athens has, in fact, become almost an empty city as the heat
wave drove a large number of Athenians to beaches while forcing
many others to stay indoors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
