<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Launches Program for Child Labor Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Ministry of Labor and
Social Protection on Tuesday officially launched a program to
eliminate child labor in the country.
</P>
<P>
The International Program for Child Labor Elimination, set up
in cooperation with the International Labor Bureau, targets a
group of 1,500 children coming from problem families, split
families or living in the streets.
</P>
<P>
Through this project, these children will be integrated in
educational institutions while child labor will be eliminated
progressively, Labor Minister Smaranda Dobrescu said.
</P>
<P>
The program, estimated to cost 600,000 U.S. dollars, will
operate for two years at national level and the actions to be
taken will focus on the families of the selected children and the
institutions involved in this field.
</P>
<P>
At present, Romania does not have relevant statistics about the
number of children working legally or illegally, but the Labor
Minister believes this phenomenon is not too widespread in the
country. Smaranda Dobrescu pointed out that 33 percent of the
families with more than two children live in poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
