<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 50 Million Dollars Invested in Romanian Disadvantaged Regions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 4 (Xinhua) -- About 1,100 billion of lei (51.64
million U.S. dollars) have been invested in 25 disadvantaged
regions in Romania since a special assistance program was
implemented nine months ago, the official Rompres news agency
reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As many as 760 commercial companies, of which 96 joint-ventures,
invested and created 13,000 new jobs in the regions characterized
by mono-industrial production structure, high unemployment rate
and weak development of infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Under the assistance program initiated by the National Agency
of Regional Development, a region will be declared "disadvantaged"
if it is a mono-industrial production structure involving more
than half of the working force, with mass lay-offs affecting more
than 25 percent of the employees, with an unemployment rate 30
percent higher than the national level, a precarious area or the
lack of communication means.
</P>
<P>
In these regions, any new investment to boost economic activity,
infrastructure and employment will benefit from customs and tax
exemption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
