<HEADLINE> Malofeyev Agrees to Takes over Belarus National Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Soviet Union coach Eduard
Malofeyev said in Minsk on Tuesday that he had agreed to take over
the Belarus national team.
</P>
<P>
58-year-old Malofeyev said:"After meeting with various
officials from the Belarus soccer federation and those from the
Sports Ministry, I agreed to take charge of the national team on a
full-time basis."
</P>
<P>
Malofeyev replaces Sergei Borovsky, who was sacked last month
following a string of poor results.
</P>
<P>
Belarus suffered three consecutive defeats to Estonia (2-0),
Bulgaria (4-1) and Andorra (2-0) in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
Belarus is in European group five with Norway, Ukraine, Poland,
Wales and Armenia for the 2002 World Cup qualifiers, which starts
in September.
</P>
<P>
Malofeyev guided the Soviet Union to the 1986 World Cup finals
in Mexico. He also coached various Soviet clubs, including Dynamo
Moscow and Dynamo Minsk, taking the latter to their only Soviet
league title in 1982. 
</P>
