<HEADLINE> Campaign Launched to Curb Illegal Drug Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China started a three-month
campaign today to combat illegal drug and food advertisements with
a notice issued by the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce (SAIT).
</P>
<P>
The notice came amidst surging complaints from consumers about
fake and exaggerated drug and food advertisements in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The offenses of such advertisements include exaggeration of
contents, coverage by the media in the form of scientific or
special reports, citing names of doctors, experts and patients
without approval, and so on, the notice pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"All these activities are violations of the existing laws and
regulations, and will be severely dealt with," the notice stressed.
</P>
<P>
The SAIT will further improve the format concerning issuance of
advertisements, and supervise advertisement releasers to comply
with the regulations on medical advertisements. Media organs which
fail to follow the format will be deprived of the right to carry
advertisements beginning July 15, the notice said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
