<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Completes Thorough Investigation of Land Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- After almost 20 years of efforts
made by the land resources authorities, China is, for the first
time, able to publish detailed information and data on its land
resources.
</P>
<P>
This was learned at a briefing here today held by the Ministry
of Land Resources to report on the results of land resources
investigations.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister Tian Fengshan, by October 31, 1996, China
had about 130 million ha of cultivated land, 10 million ha of
parks, 228 million ha of forests, 266 million ha of pasture, 24
million ha of land for residential and industrial use, and 5.47
million ha of land covered by roads and other transport facilities.
The rest are waters and untapped land.
</P>
<P>
The area of cultivated land published this time is 35 million
ha larger than in previous reports, because a unitary standard was
adopted in the surveying, according to Tian.
</P>
<P>
China has six million ha of cultivated land situated on
mountain slopes at 25 degrees and above. All the sloping farmland
should be returned to forests in a planned way so as to improve
the environment, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the survey, launched in 1980 and involving more than
500,000 professionals, shows that the country's per-capita
cultivated land stands at 0.106 ha, less than half of the world's
average, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
