<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dunhuang Art Exhibition Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Dunhuang Art Exhibition, the
largest of its kind in the world, opened here today at the Museum
of Chinese History, featuring replicas of the Dunhuang caves and
original sutras found in the secret Library Cave.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, organized by the State Cultural Heritage
Administration and the Gansu provincial government, also displays
dozens of precious cultural relics and delicate copies of the well-
known Dunhuang frescoes.
</P>
<P>
China has arranged the two-month show to commemorate the
centennial of the discovery of the Dunhuang Library Cave.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits include four full-size replicas of caves at
Dunhuang, copies of 30 murals, ten copies of figurines, 14
authentic sutras and ten copies of sutras, six genuine paintings
and 44 reproductions, as well as more than 80 photographs of
Dunhuang relics preserved both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the exhibition, Minister of Culture
Sun Jiazheng said that, as a World Heritage site, the Dunhuang
Mogao Grottoes and their art reflect glorious achievements made by
ancient Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The Mogao Grottoes of Dunhuang, popularly known as the Thousand
Buddha Caves, were carved out of sandstone cliffs stretching for
about 1,600 meters along the eastern side of Mingsha Hill, 25
kilometers southeast of Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
A Tang Dynasty (618-907) inscription records that the first
cave in the Mogao Grottoes was dug in 366. Despite erosion and man-
made destruction, the 492 caves are well preserved, with frescoes
covering an area of 45,000 square meters, more than 2,000 colored
sculptured figures and five wooden eaves overhanging the caves.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, Taoist priest Wang Yuanlu discovered a secret cave
there containing more than 50,000 sutras, documents and paintings
of nearly 10 dynasties, ranging from the 4th to the 11th centuries.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that we have put relics from the sutra
cave on display. All the authentic relics were collected from
Beijing, Shanghai, Sichuan and Gansu," said Fan Jinshi, director
of the Dunhuang Academy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an official website for the exhibition, www.
dunhuang2000.com, was initiated this morning, introducing the
latest news for the commemoration and the exhibition itself. The
website will remain active after the exhibition closes, one of the
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Artistic Pilgrimage (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Modern Chinese make a pilgrimage to
rather than visit the Dunhuang Art Exhibition, which opened today
in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Four full-size replicas of the most famous Dunhuang caves in
northwest China's Gansu Province have been set up at the world's
largest-ever show on Dunhuang art at the Museum of Chinese History.
</P>
<P>
After a half-year of refurbishment, the museum saw flocks of
people braving a summer storm today to show their enthusiasm about
Dunhuang art and its studies.
</P>
<P>
Before the exhibition, most Chinese had no opportunity to view
the treasured documents formerly preserved in the Library Cave of
the Dunhuang Mogao Grottos.
</P>
<P>
Fan Jinshi, director of the Dunhuang Academy, who has
masterminded the work for the exhibition over the past two years,
said that the Dunhuang Art Exhibition is one of the most important
successes in her life.
</P>
<P>
Academic circles regard the exhibition as the most outstanding
art show on Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits include four full-size replicas of Dunhuang caves,
copies of 30 murals, ten copies of figurines, 14 authentic sutras
and ten sutra copies, six genuine paintings and 44 reproductions,
as well as more than 80 photographs of Dunhuang relics preserved
both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Museum of Chinese History and the Gansu Provincial Museum
provided a silk painting each, dating back more than 1,000 years,
for the exhibition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Artistic Pilgrimage (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, the Dunhuang Academy arranged with many museums in
other countries to borrow Dunhuang documents they are preserving,
and sometimes replicas.
</P>
<P>
More than 50,000 cultural relics from the Library Cave are
spread throughout the world, with Russia having 19,000 pieces and
Britain maintaining 13,000.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition organizers went all out to garner 42 exhibits
copying the original precious sutras and pictures kept in Western
museums.
</P>
<P>
"The precious relics amaze me with their delicacy," said Jing
Junjian, an economist with the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
(CASS)
</P>
<P>
The replica of the 17th cave, or the Library Cave, attracts
most of the visitors.
</P>
<P>
A Tang Dynasty inscription records that the first cave in the
Mogao Grottoes was made in 366. Despite erosion and man-made
destruction, the 492 caves are well preserved, with frescoes
covering 45,000 sq m, more than 2,000 colored sculptured figures
and five wooden eaves overhanging the caves.
</P>
<P>
After the discovery of the Libary Cave, the explorers Aurel
Stein and Paul Pelliot took many Dunhuang documents to Western
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
