<HEADLINE> Most of Angolan Districts Under Government Control: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has taken
control of 92 percent of the country's 157 districts, said
spokesman for the Council of the Republic Domingos Culolo on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion was reached after analyzing the country's
current political, military, social and economic situation, he
said at the end of a meeting of the Council of the Republic, a
consultation body of Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
According to Culolo, also Attorney General of the war-torn
country, the current situation throughout the country is improving
and in some places " the movement of people and goods is on the
rise".
</P>
<P>
The conventional war was over as the rebels of the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) led by Jonas
Savimbi retreated into the bush and sought a guerrilla war, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment," the spokesman said, "the Angolan Armed Forces
are in a phase of re-organization, in a bid to face up to the
guerrilla war that Jonas Savimbi is waging against the Angolan
people."
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said most of the districts under the government
control locate in the coastal provinces and the central highland,
after the government troops expelled the rebels out of most cities
in the central provinces such as Huambo and Bie in a mass
offensive last year.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA rebels are still controlling some districts in the
eastern areas bordering Zambia, including the Moxico province.
</P>
</TEXT>
