<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Palestinian State Without Israeli Consent: Israeli Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Justice Minister Yossi
Beilin said Tuesday morning that without Israelis consent, the
Palestinians will not succeed in unilaterally declaring an
independent state in September.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio, Beilin added that even if Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat makes a unilateral announcement, an
independent Palestinian state will not be really established
without Israel's agreement.
</P>
<P>
Without Israel's recognition, he said, the Palestinian state
will exist only on paper, even if "the whole world recognizes the
new-born state."
</P>
<P>
Beilin was responding to the decision made by the Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO) Central Council Monday night to
support Arafat's plan to declare independence on September 13.
</P>
<P>
According to peace agreements between Israel and the
Palestinians, the two sides should reach a final peace accord by
this September.
</P>
<P>
However, the talks, aiming at resolving thorny issues such as
the fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees,
border, security and water, have remained stagnant in the past few
weeks, dimming the hope of reaching a final agreement on time.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials believe that Arafat is using the threat of a
unilateral declaration of statehood to pressure Israel into
accepting his demands regarding the final-phase Israeli troops
withdrawal from the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the further release
of Palestinian prisoners, and the dismantling of Jewish settlements
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Some Palestinians are also worried that a unilateral declaration
might trigger violent clashes between Israel soldiers and the
Palestinians, which will do benefit only to Israel's hawkish
politicians and draw the peace process years back.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Shaul
Mofaz has threatened that if such violence erupted, the IDF will
use tanks and gunships to quell it.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the major sponsor of Middle East peace
process, had told Palestinian officials that it does not approve of
a unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
