<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Palestinians Pessimistic of Peace Agreement On Time: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A majority of the Palestinians
believed that Israel and the Palestinians could not reach a peace
agreement by September as stipulated in the Sharm el Sheikh interim
deal, a poll result released here Tuesday indicated.
</P>
<P>
Some 59.8 percent of the Palestinians said the two sides could
not strike a final peace deal by that time while only 17.8 percent
believed they could meet the target, showed the poll, conducted by
Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC) on June 23 among 1,
200 Palestinians from the West Bank, Gaza Strip and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As regards the negotiation positions of the Palestinian
leadership and the public opinion on some of the suggested
compromises being talked about in the media, it appeared that the
Palestinians were more inclined to holding on to the declared
positions of the Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
Only 3.7 percent of the interviewees supported the idea of
solving the Jewish settlement problem by giving up part of the
occupied territories where settlements have been set up and
creating a Palestinian state on the remaining 70-80 percent of
land. In contrast, 64.7 percent of those interviewed rejected this
solution.
</P>
<P>
As for the refugee issue, only 10.8 percent of the interviewed
said they will accept a solution suggested by Israel that most of
the refugees will be naturalized in their host countries and only a
small number could return through a family reunification program.
</P>
<P>
Some 48.8 percent of the Palestinian interviewed rejected this
solution while 34.9 percent were not decided on it.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the issue of Jerusalem, 62.3 percent said they will
reject a solution by which the city remains under Israeli
sovereignty while the Palestinians are given a presence on its
outskirts.
</P>
<P>
As for the declaration of an independent Palestinian state in
September, most of the Palestinians, 51.6 percent, said they could
not expect the Palestinian leadership to do so, although 48.3
percent saw that a state should be declared in any case while 22.3
percent supported declaring the state only after reaching an
agreement with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
