<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Dips Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso closed
marginally lower against the U.S. dollar Tuesday, dragged by
weaker regional currencies and the persisting negative news in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The peso closed at 43.535 pesos against the U.S. dollar, weaker
compared to the previous close of 43.53 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Traders said bomb threats in the country continued to be a main
concern for investors. The weak peso was further weighed down by
weak regional currencies, led by the Indonesian rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The peso was traded Tuesday between 43.520 pesos and 43.600
pesos on a turnover volume of 89 million dollars transacted at the
Philippine Dealing System.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla said
Tuesday he expects the peso to stabilize between 42 to 42.50 pesos
against the U.S. dollar and there is no need for government to
intervene the exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Medalla said the country's trade and current account surplus
which is the result of a strong export performance and earnings
sent home by overseas Filipino workers will all contribute to
ringing the exchange rate down.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the market would quickly be restored as soon as
major military operations in Mindanao come to a halt and the peace
talks with the Moro Islamic Liberation Front starts.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Rafael Buenaventura, governor of the Central
Bank of the Philippines, stressed that the central bank will not
intervene even the peso further shed off its value to almost 44
pesos to a dollar.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura said the dollar shortage in the local market is
caused by speculations in the market due to the on-going conflict
in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
He assured the public that the peso value is still tolerable at
this level so that there is no cause for too much worry at this
time when the country's cash position is manageable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
