<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zoff Quits as Coach after Berlusconi Criticism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Italy's national soccer coach Dino
Zoff resigned Wednesday following criticism from Opposition and
Forza Italia leader Silvio Berlusconi, owner of the first division
club AC Milan, that he was to blame for losing the Euro 2000 final
against France on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zoff's resignation came as a surprise to soccer federation
officials who did not expect him to react this way to the
accusations from Berlusconi that he was "unworthy and amateur" and
had show a "lack of intelligence" in his decision for the final in
Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
"I know what the consequences will be and I know what people
will say and what they will suggest", Zoff said in announcing his
decision, "I will not accept lessons on dignity from Mr.
Berlusconi".
</P>
<P>
"I do not understand why one has to denigrate the work of
others", Zoff continued, "I have been offended as a man,
denigrated in public by Berlusconi to whom I will respond in
person".
</P>
<P>
"I must make certain decisions and they will cost me," he told
the press, "I know what will happen. They will try to turn this
around and say I just took advantage of the situation. I know I
will not come out of this well, in any case, I have experience. I
should have been much harder, I know what life is like, I do not
want to go any further.
</P>
<P>
Zoff also announced that he did not intend to sue Berlusconi
for his statements.
</P>
<P>
On learning of Zoff's decision, at his home in Milan,
Berlusconi told Italian news agency Ansa "I can't believe it. I
never offended anyone, much less Zoff. I did not denigrate his
work. I made a technical criticism of which I remain deeply
convinced Among the first to comment on Zoff's decision was the
coach of Italy's Under 21 side and his possible successor, Marco
Tardelli, who said "I am very saddened and I think this epilogue
is unjust. Although I would never allow myself to judge his
decision, it is clear that he comes way the big winner".
</P>
<P>
Tardelli went on to add that he did not think that Zoff was "
leaving because of what was said yesterday. Known him as I do, I
believe his decision was well though out".
</P>
<P>
After refusing to speculate on his own chances of filling Zoff'
s place on the bench, Tardelli said of his former team-mate "Dino
was a great winner with the national team, as a player and as a
coach". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
