<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abnormal Weather Afflicts China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A series of climatic anomalies
plagued China during the first half of this year, leading to
climatic disasters in some regions, said Wen Kegang, director of
the China Meteorological Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 sand storms hit northern China this spring,
interfering with transportation and people's daily lives, and even
causing casualties in some regions.
</P>
<P>
From March to May, the average high temperature across China
was second only to the same period of 1998 since 1961, and the
temperature in north China was especially high, said Wen.
</P>
<P>
High temperature, together with low rainfall, caused serious
droughts in northern China. From February to April, the average
precipitation in north China was only 23 mm, the lowest in 50
years.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, about 20 million hectares of land suffered from
drought, and over 20 million people were short of drinking water
during the three months, according to Wen.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, rain storms hit some regions in the south of
the Yangtze River and caused flooding in some places, affecting
more than 85,000 hectares of farmland and millions of people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
