<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Qatar and Syria have agreed to establish a joint free
trade zone (FTZ) by applying gradual exemptions on products of each
other country.
</P>
<P>
Ali Hasan al-Khalf, director of the Qatari Finance, Economy and
Trade Ministry's Economic Affairs Administration, said the
agreement involved an immediate exemption of tariffs, taxes and
non-governmental restrictions on farm and animal products and
natural wealth between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On other goods, a 50-percent exemption is to be in effect as of
January 1, 2000, 70-percent from January 2002, and 100-percent from
January 2003.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian government has adopted an "emergency
plan" with an aim to eliminate unemployment in three years.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 80 billion liras (1.65 billion U.S.
dollars) for the anti-unemployment project, with 15 billion liras
(309.3 million dollars) of the fund to be provided by the Postal
Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to amend the Labor Law to ban children
under 16 from work and allow only qualified laborers to work in the
public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Kamal Hassoouneh, Palestinian co-chairman of the
Turkish-Palestinian Business Council, said before the Council's
meeting in Istanbul Monday that the Council is a joint platform
that will contribute to improving bilateral business relations in
the future.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinians consider Turkey as an important partner
in the Palestinian economic development, adding that the
Palestinian side would like to purchase Turkish iron and steel,
food and textile products and export marble and glass to Turkish
market.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish industrial conglomerate Koc Holding and
Norwegian national oil company Statoil have signed a preliminary
agreement on natural gas cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Koc Holding wanted to be more effective in the natural gas
sector and Statoil wanted to enter the Turkish market with a
powerful partner.
</P>
<P>
Koc and Statoil will carry out their preparations for planned
joint projects and meet in Istanbul in October to unveil details of
the proposed cooperation. 
</P>
