<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Get Richer, Poorest Go Backward in Australia: Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The poorest people in Australia
are now worse off than they were in 1985, while the richest 1
percent have increased their real earnings by more than 30 percent,
the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ABS annual social trends report revealed that most
Australians went backward in the late 1980s as inflation easily
outstripped wage increases.
</P>
<P>
It was only in 1990 that people on average incomes began
reversing the slide and average income earners are now about 10
percent better off than they were in 1985, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
However, the poorest 10 percent only saw their living standards
start to pick up in 1996 and by 1998 they were still earning less,
in real terms, than they had 13 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, the living standards of the wealthiest 1 percent
have been increasing since 1987 and by 1998 they were over 30
percent higher, on average, than it had been 13 year earlier.
</P>
<P>
That has dramatically widened the gap between the rich and the
poor, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 percent Australians now earn 1.7 times more than
average income earners, while the poorest 10 percent receive less
than two-thirds the average income, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the poorest 10 percent and average wage earners
widened by 9.7 percent between 1985 and 1998 while that between
the wealthiest 10 percent and middle income earners increased by 5.
5 percent, the ABS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
