<HEADLINE> Male, Female Wage Inequality Widens in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The gap between male and female
earnings in Australia is widening, with women now being paid just
83 percent as much as men, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (
ABS) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The annual social trends report from the ABS revealed that
women's base pay, over-award pay, performance pay and overtime
rates all fell behind those for men between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The average base pay of women in May 1998 was 91 percent of the
male base pay, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
However, four years earlier the base pay of women was 94
percent of the male rate.
</P>
<P>
Women in 1998 received just 44 percent of the over-award
payments, 19 percent of the performance pay bonuses and 21
percent of the overtime payments made to men.
</P>
<P>
Women's total earnings are just 83 percent of male earnings,
down from 85 percent in 1994, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The gap is fairly consistent across all professions with one
big exception. Women managers and administrators are paid 6
percent more than their male counterparts despite the fact that
they make up just 21 percent of the profession, the ABS said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
