<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Ages, Becomes More Diverse in 20th Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia became an older and more
diverse society in the 20th century, the Australian Bureau of
Statistics (ABS) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The social trends report of the ABS compared statistics of 1901
with more recent data to chart population changes across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
The report found that the median age for Australians in 1901
was 22.6 years, compared with 34.9 years in 1999. The expected
median age in 2051 is 44.1 years.
</P>
<P>
By 2051, Australia's population would reach 25 million, with
almost one in four people aged 65 years or older, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
In 1901, the population was 3.8 million, compared with 18.9
million in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the century, Australians were predominantly
Christian and born either in Australia, the United Kingdom or
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
But at the end of the century, about 16 percent of Australians
were born in countries other than these three.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 78 percent of Australians said they were Christian,
compared with 98 percent in 1901, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The ABS reported that Australia was a male-dominated society at
the dawn of the 20th century and males comprised 52 percent of the
general population in 1901.
</P>
<P>
But it found a different Australia at the close of the 20th
century, with women now outnumbering men at 50.2 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
The report also found that Australians were living closer
together and had drifted toward major cities throughout the
century.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 100 years, Australians have increasingly made
their homes in cities.
</P>
<P>
In 1901, almost half the population lived on rural properties
or in towns with fewer than 3,000 people, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
But by 1996, 53 percent of Australians lived in cities with
more than 1 million people and only 18 percent of the population
lived on rural properties or in small towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0143 </DOCNO>
