<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Uses His Influence to Win World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Former South African president
Nelson Mandela revealed on Tuesday that he was still playing a key
role in South Africa's bid for the 2006 soccer World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, speaking on South African radio, said he had been
asked by Sports Minister Balfour Ngconde and the South African
2006 bid committee to use his influence this week to win the
country two more crucial votes on the panel that decides the bid.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he had seen the technical report from soccer's
world governing body, FIFA, on all the countries competing to host
the World Cup and South Africa and Germany had been well ranked.
</P>
<P>
"That had raised my hopes but let's not exaggerate those hopes
because there are 25 countries who has to vote for the winner and
we are only sure of 12 countries are in favor of us."
</P>
<P>
South Africa needed at least 13 votes in order to win the bid.
</P>
<P>
"We are left with two days to get the 13th number, when I leave
here (the radio studio) I am going to phone two countries to
request them to favor us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela refused to name the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Winning the bid was very important for economic growth in South
Africa as it would bring billions of rand in foreign currency into
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that we get the bid because not only sport
will benefit but all South Africans," Mandela said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
