<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FPDA Ministers Vows to Keep FPDA Relevant to Regional Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The 4th Five Power Defense
Arrangements Defense Ministers Meeting closed here Tuesday after
agreeing to keep FPDA relevant to the security of Singapore,
Malaysia and the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the agreement at a press conference at the end of
the one-day meeting, Singapore Deputy Prime Minister and Minister
for Defense Tony Tan said the discussions by the ministers covered
the regional security situation and the development in the FPDA
and its future direction.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated their commitment to the FPDA and agreed to work
closely together to ensure that FPDA remains relevant to the
security of Singapore and Malaysia and the long-term stability of
the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Tan, attending the meeting were Australian
Defense Minister John Moore, Malaysian Defense Minister Dato' Seri
Mohd Najib bin Tun Haji Abdul Razak, New Zealand Defense Minister
Mark Burton and British Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for
Defense Lewis Moonie.
</P>
<P>
The ministers affirmed the role of the FPDA in the defense of
Malaysia and Singapore and agreed that it is time for FPDA
exercises to progress to the next stage of development, he said.
He noted that the operational nature of the FPDA is evolving from
air defense to more combined and joint activities with the
geographical coverage of the arrangements remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the regional security environment, Tan said the ministers
noted the significant changes and much improvement in the
environment since the last defense ministers meeting in Kuala
Lumpur in 1997.
</P>
<P>
While answering questions, Tan said cross-border terrorist
activities were one of the concerns the ministers expressed at the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
