<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weapon Stealers in Malaysia Take 2 Men Hostage: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The heavily armed
impersonators who stole weapons from two army camps in Malaysia's
northern state of Perak on Sunday have taken two men hostage,
Inspector General of Police Norian Mai said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two men were abducted while picking durian near Sauk in the
state, where the armed group went into hiding after the weapon
stealing.
</P>
<P>
The whereabouts of the group was detected following a public
tip-off and a massive combined police-military operation is under
way to track down the group, the police chief told reporters in
Gerik where the two army camps are located, according to Bernama
news agency.
</P>
<P>
But he clarified earlier reports that an exchange of fire took
place between the group and security forces, saying, "There was no
exchange of fire. We believed they fired on their own, just to
shoot... Maybe they want to familiarize with the (new) arsenal."
</P>
<P>
He said the authorities would ensure that the thieves get no
opportunity to use the weapons to threaten national security.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations so far indicated that the motive of the
raid on the army camps was "purely criminal intent," he said,
adding however that he did not rule out political motives.
</P>
<P>
"We believe some among them have knowledge of military affairs,
as obvious from the methods of their raid," the police chief said,
pointing out that they were well-versed in military methods and
procedures.
</P>
<P>
To a question on whether servicemen were involved, Norian said,
"I cannot confirm. We are still investigating."
</P>
<P>
The group of 15 impersonators raided the two camps within three
hours Sunday and made off with a haul of more than 100 M16 rifles
and thousands of rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The security forces cordoned off the area where the group went
into hiding after the discovery of three four-wheeled-drive
vehicles believed to have been used by them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
