<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Share prices on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
closed broadly higher Tuesday on technical rebound, but trading
remained thin.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index rose 13.94
points or 1.76 percent to 807.87, the all-share Emas Index added 2.
92 points to 202.4, the Industrial Index gained 20.46 points to 1,
402.39 and the Second Board Index rose 1.56 points to 213.3.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover declined to 79.794 million shares worth 305.
73 million ringgit (80.45 million U.S. dollars) from 89.466
million shares valued at 361.879 million ringgit (95.23 million
dollars) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australian stocks closed slightly higher Tuesday as
renewed interest in technology companies compensated for losses in
resources and banks.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed three points higher at 3,259.5.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index closed gaining 11.9 points at 5,710.1
while the All Resources Index was down 8.1 points at 1,309.6.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 780.37 million shares at a value of 1.56
billion Australian dollars (936 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- The New Zealand sharemarket closed lower here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NZSE40 Index ended six points lower at 2,045 with a
turnover of 100 million NZ dollars (46.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index Tuesday
lost 2.6 points to close at 316.66.
</P>
<P>
Some 209 million shares worth 2.18 billion baht (56.59 million
U.S. dollars) changed hands Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The SET index Monday lost 6.43 point from Friday to close at
319.26.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Share prices closed mixed on the Singapore Stock
Market Tuesday as the local bourse became directionless because of
Wall Street's closure for the U.S. Independence Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) inched down 1.61 points
to close at 2,072.42 in moderate trading.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 476.51 million units worth
495.31 million Singapore dollars (285.86 million U.S. dollars).
There were 167 gainers against 142 losers with 238 counters
unchanged. 
</P>
