<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunday Blasts in Chechnya Kill 33 Russian Servicemen: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A series of terrorist blasts staged
by rebels in Chechnya killed 33 Russian servicemen and wounded 83
others with three missing, Russian presidential aide on Chechnya,
Sergei Yastrzhembsky, announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is the final figures of the federal units' losses in
these acts of terror," excluding the casualties of civilians and
rebel kamikazes, he told the press.
</P>
<P>
The losses of the Russian Defense Ministry: three killed and
eight wounded; of the Interior Ministry policemen: 24 killed, 56
wounded and three missing; and of the Interior Troops: six killed
and 19 wounded, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
At the same day, First Deputy Chief of the Russian General
Staff Valery Manilov confirmed the number of the federal losses.
</P>
<P>
Monday, Russian news agencies reported that at least three
civilians and one kamikaze bomb-truck driver also died in an
explosion in the city of Argun, 10 kilometers southeast of the
Chechen capital of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Manilov told Russia's independent NTV television on Tuesday
that the efforts to combat terrorism in Chechnya must be
intensified and more effective security measures must be taken.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that large rebel groupings will be destroyed before
the end of the summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
