<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (RECAST) Northwest China to Introduce More Water Saving Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River Water
Conservation Committee is planning to popularize more water saving
measures in the drought-prone northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The measures are expected to help local people save 5.8 billion
cubic meters of water in the areas of the upper and middle reaches
of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
According to proposals put forward by experts, irrigation
canals in northwest China would be upgraded to help ease the water
shortage. And more pipes would be introduced for the irrigation
purpose.
</P>
<P>
Experts also proposed that the water quota be cut down to
restrict flood irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Most parts of northwest China, including the Xinjiang Uygur,
Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous regions and the
provinces of Qinghai, Gansu and Shaanxi, are drought-prone and
short of water resources, although more than 3,000 reservoirs have
been built in the areas since 1949, when New China was founded.
</P>
<P>
The experts noted that water shortage will become a bottleneck
in the economic development of the areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
