<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Readies Ballistic Missile Launching Pads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran has built five launching pads
for ballistic missiles, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With these launching pads, Iran now ranks among the leading
military powers of the region, the news agency quoted Rahim Safavi,
commander-in-chief of the elite Islamic Revolution Corps, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
But the general did not give details.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian military, eager to become self-sufficient in
armaments, is regularly testing different types of missiles. The
last test was conducted in March, when a surface-to-air missile was
launched in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
In July 1998, Iran successfully test-fired "Shahab-3"(Meteor-3)
missile with a range of 1,300 kilometers, which meant it can hit
targets in Israel, Saudi Arabia and the United States forces in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Faster GCC Economic Growth Expected: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- High oil prices have added impetus
to the sluggish economic growth in the six Gulf Arabic states that
make up the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), the Dubai-based daily "
Gulf News" reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said a report released Monday by the Gulf Organization
for Industrial Consulting (GOIC) indicated that average economic
growth of the GCC members rose to 2.21 percent in 1999 from 1.03
percent the previous year, and an increase to 3.8 percent in 2000
was on the cards.
</P>
<P>
The report said the six states, namely Saudi Arabia, the United
Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain, Kuwait and Oman, showed economic
recovery in 1999 as their total gross domestic product (GDP)
increased by 6 billion U.S. dollars to 266.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industrial forecasts which expect average oil prices in 2000 to
calm down to 16-18 dollars per barrel would provide a good chance
for the GCC member countries to see further GDP growth, estimated
the report.
</P>
<P>
"If those expectations come true, the growth rate would rise to
3.8 percent in 2000," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that preliminary figures showed a rise in GCC
oil revenues to over 70 billion dollars in 1999 from 42 billion
dollars in 1998 and expected a further upward trend this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite a surge in oil prices in the fourth quarter of 1999, GCC
governments "adopted conservative financial policies anticipating a
decline in oil revenues down to 40.2 billion dollars last year,"
the report added.
</P>
<P>
The Doha-based GOIC was established in the Qatari capital in
1976 with the objective of developing industries of the member
states, which include the six GCC members and Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Treasury Raises Growth Prediction for This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Finance Ministry has
raised its economic growth prediction for this year from 4.0
percent, as made a few months ago, to 4.5 percent in its latest
forecast.
</P>
<P>
The revised forecast will be presented to the cabinet on Sunday
in preparation for discussions of the 2001 budget, reported an
Israeli newspaper on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The English edition of Ha'aretz said the new forecast also
predicts a growth of 4.5 percent in 2001. In 1998 and 1999, growth
was 2.2 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Israeli economy has been enjoying a growth rate as high as 6
percent over the past few months. However, the treasury said the
rapid pace cannot be maintained.
</P>
<P>
It also predicts that unemployment will finally decline this
year to an average of 8.5 percent, after a steady rise in three
consecutive years. The prediction for 2001 is 8.1 percent, which
compares with 8.9 percent last year, 8.5 percent in 1998 and 7.6
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports will increase at a rapid 15.7 percent rate this year.But
the treasury estimated that the rate will drop to 9.5 percent in
2001, similar to the rate of 9.7 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, said the paper, all of these rosy forecasts rest on a
number of optimistic assumptions, many of which the government can
not control. These include the arrival of 6,000 new immigrants in
2001, the absence of any major financial crises outside Israel, and
continued stability on world stock markets -- especially Nasdaq in
the U.S., where most Israeli high-tech companies raise their
capital.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the forecast assumes that the government will
achieve a number of economic policy goals, which include deficit
and debt reduction, keeping public-sector wages at their current
level, implementation of a sweeping tax reform package and a
reduction in the number of foreign workers. It also assumes that
there will be no political crises, such as new elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
