<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Shortage in Kenya's Capital Enters Third Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The acute water shortage in the
Kenyan capital Nairobi entered its third month Tuesday with
water-borne diseases imminent.
</P>
<P>
The residents in the city warned that an outbreak of
water-borne diseases like cholera was impending unless water
supply is restored immediately in the city with a population of 2
million.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded the Nairobi City Council to announce a water
 rationing program to enable them to know the time to draw water,
the East African Standard newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
They said that the program will save them from being exploited
by unscrupulous water vendors, who usually sold a 20 litre
container of water at 30 shillings (around 0.4 U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
City residents complained that the vendors had capitalized on
the water shortage to make quick profits from people desperate for
water.
</P>
<P>
"People can survive without electricity but they can not
survive without water as it is an essential commodity," said Mama
Njeri, a resident.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi City Council recently worked out a rationing plan but
the schedule has not been made public.
</P>
<P>
Due to the current drought in the Horn of Africa, water
shortage has reigned throughout the east African country and more
than 2.2 million Kenyans are threatened by starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Faces Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is facing a shortage
of food and a decline in the production of cash crops such as
tobacco, cotton and sisal in its mainland regions, newspapers here
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Agriculture and Cooperatives William Kusila was
quoted as saying that the decrease was due to drought, fall of
prices in the world market and snags in supplying inputs to
farmers.
</P>
<P>
The house preliminary statistics on food crop production for
the 1999/ 2000 season show that Tanzania produced 91 percent of
its food requirements. Food crop production can reach 6.68 million
tons while estimates of food requirements are 7.36 million tons,
leaving a deficit of some 681,000 tons of food countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Eleven out of 20 regions on Mainland Tanzania have been hit by
food shortage, Kusila said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the nation has recorded an increase in the
production of commercial crops such as cashew nuts, tea,
pyrethrum, coffee and sugar during the 1999/2000 season compared
to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the backbone of Tanzania's economy and its
principal source of income, providing about 50 percent of its GDP
and more than 90 percent of its export earnings.
</P>
<P>
However, the eastern African country remains vulnerable to
hunger and starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Remains Ban on Kenya's Fish Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Planning Minister Gideon
Ndambuki has said that the European Union officials had assured
him that they would lift the two-year-old ban on Kenyan fish
export as soon as its fishing sector met the hygiene standards.
</P>
<P>
The fishing industry still failed to implement the hygiene
requirements by the EU, Ndambuki was quoted by the newspaper Daily
Nation as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I can authoritatively report that the EU is not against Kenya
as a country; what they are asking the industry is to ensure that
chemical use and unhygienic practices are rooted out in order to
enable them immediately to lift the ban," Ndambuki said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The export of fresh fish from Kenya to the EU was banned in
January 1998 for not complying with basic hygiene rules after a
cholera outbreak in the Lake Victoria region in the wake of El
Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Kenya exported about 52,000 tons of fish, mostly Nile
perch from Lake Victoria, valued at 862 million shillings (about
11.5 million U.S. dollars), mainly to Germany and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0206 </DOCNO>
