<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Two Jet Trainers Go Missing Over Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Two jet trainers of Japan's Air Self-
Defense Force (ASDF) went missing with three crew members aboard
on Tuesday morning over the sea off Miyagi Prefecture,
northeastern Japan, the Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The two T-4 jets of the ASDF's Blue Impulse acrobatic flight
team disappeared from radar around 10.20 a.m. (0120 GMT) while
returning to the ASDF's Matsushima base in the prefecture after
training with four other jets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The jets went missing over the Pacific some 25 kilometers
southeast of the base, the report said, adding that ASDF
helicopters and Japan Coast Guard patrol boats were searching the
area.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Blue Impulse team was established in 1960 to give
acrobatic performances. The team currently comprises eight T-4
planes and 11 pilots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Mori Re-elected Prime Minister EDS-UPDATES with upper house approval, writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Both houses of the Japanese
parliament on Tuesday re-elected Yoshiro Mori as Japan's new prime
minister, paving the way for the formation of a new cabinet later
in the day.
</P>
<P>
Mori won the premiership votes in both chambers of the Diet (
parliament) with the support of his ruling Liberal Democratic
Party and the party's two junior coalition partners, the New
Komeito party and the New Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
Mori collected 284 of the 479 votes cast in the 480-member
House of Representatives, and 133 of the 242 votes in the 252-
member House of Councilors.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary votes were held on the first day of a three-
day special Diet session following the June 25 general election.
</P>
<P>
The lineup for Mori's new cabinet is expected to be announced
shortly after 6 p.m. (0900 GMT).
</P>
<P>
In the new cabinet, Mori is expected to retain Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa and Foreign Minister Yohei Kono, who will chair
the ministerial meetings in Fukuoka and Miyazaki respectively,
ahead of the July 21-23 Group of Eight summit in Okinawa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
