<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Introduce Water Saving Project in Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River Water
Conservancy Committee is planning to popularize water saving
techniques in the drought-prone northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The measures are expected to help local people save 5.8 billion
cubic meters of water in the upper and middle reaches of Yellow
River and in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
According to proposals put forward by experts, irrigation
canals in northwest China would be upgrated to meet the demand of
water resistance. And more pipes would be introduced to channel
water for the purpose of water saving.
</P>
<P>
Experts also proposed that the water quota be cut down in order
to restrict flood irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Most parts of northwest China, including the Xinjiang Uygur,
Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous regions and the
provinces of Qinghai, Gansu and Shaanxi, are drought-prone and
short of water resources, although more than 3,000 reservoirs have
been built in the region since 1949, when New China was founded.
</P>
<P>
The experts noted that water shortage will become a bottleneck
in the economic development of the region. Water saving and
efficient use of water resources should be widely propagated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Panda Cubs to Settle in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Two giant panda cubs from southwest
China's Sichuan Province -- Mei Xiang and Tian Tian -- have been
selected as gifts to the United States soon.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Wolong Nature Reserve disclosed today that
the female Mei Xiang is two years old and weighs 60 kilograms,
while her future husband Tian Tian is one year older and weighs 95
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Mei Xiang is good-looking and well-shaped, while the male Tian
Tian is rather shy and honest. Both pandas are in excellent health
conditions, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Although the exact leaving date of two pandas has not been
fixed yet, the two pandas are scheduled to spend 10 years in the U.
S. for scientific research in panda breeding, according to an
agreement reached between the China Wildlife Conservation
Association and the National Zoological Park (NZP).
</P>
<P>
The official said that a panel led by Lisa Stevens, the
associate curator of biological programs of the NZP, had come to
see the pandas earlier this year and were very satisfied with
their conditions.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 giant pandas, facing the danger of extinction, now
inhabit the mountain areas of the Sichuan Basin.
</P>
<P>
China has sent two giant pandas to U.S. as friendly envoys in
1970s. Last year, Hsing-Hsing, the male giant panda died of kidney
failure in the Washington Zoo and the Americans were very sad
about it, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
