<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said on Monday that he is
not sure whether he has peace partner in the Palestinians, and
hinted that if there is a U.S.-brokered summit it is unlikely to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Israel has made clear to the Palestinians that it
won't accept unilateral steps, such as an establishment of a state.
However, Barak said if such a move takes place, Israel will respond
by annexing the large population blocks in the settlements and
establishing a security zone in the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- After a day of stormy debate, the Israeli Knesset
(Parliament) Monday night approved the first reading of the Tal
bill on the deferment of the conscription of ultra-orthodox yeshiva
students by the Israel Defense Forces. The vote was 52 in favor and
43 against, with seven abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The vote also turned into a test of confidence in the government
of Ehud Barak, following a suggestion to do so by Knesset member
Roman Bronfman.
</P>
<P>
In response to the challenge, Knesset members of the ruling One
Israel bloc who were violently opposed to the bill, such as
Environment Minister Dalia Itzik, decided to support the bill.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel may impose a ban on irrigating public parks and
private gardens in the latter part of the summer due to the
worsening water crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Water Council Monday said this ban would be in addition to a
moratorium on washing cars with hoses and further cutbacks in water
quotas to farmers. The Council also recommended that these
proposals be incorporated into municipal by-laws, which local
authorities would then enforce.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Monday found himself faced
with strong opposition from his own party colleagues on the issue
of the Tal bill on conscripting yeshiva students into the Israel
Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
In a stormy meeting of the ruling One Israel faction, a number
of party members voiced their opposition to the legislation and
demanded that they be permitted to vote freely, arguing that the
issue was a matter of conscience. Nonetheless, Barak rejected the
request and imposed parliamentary discipline on all members of his
faction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
