<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's security forces
Tuesday intercepted a band of impersonators who stole weapons from
two military camps in the northern state of Perak last Sunday and
exchanged fire with them in the state, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
A combined police-military massive manhunt tracked the weapon
stealers hiding in Sauk in the state early Tuesday and the
security forces were fired upon when they were approaching the
group's hideout and a 90-minute skirmish ensued, Bernama news
agency quoted the sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
No reports of casualties in the exchange of fire were so far
available.
</P>
<P>
The security forces have cordoned off the area since Monday
night after the discovery of three four-wheeled-drive vehicles
believed to have been used by 15 men to cart away more than 100
M16 rifles and thousands of rounds of ammunition from two army
camps in Gerik in Perak state.
</P>
<P>
The security forces called for reinforcement Tuesday morning
upon locating the group's hideout among orchards in the area.
</P>
<P>
Several villagers in Sauk said they heard gunfire and
explosions in the early hours of Tuesday and saw troops moving
past their homes,according to Bernama. 
