<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Exports Grow by 6.7 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Exports of the Philippines for May
grew by 6.7 percent to 2.931 billion U.S. dollars from 2.747
billion dollars during the same month of 1999, the National
Statistics Office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, total receipts for the first five
months of 2000 amounted to 14.206 billion dollars, 9.7 percent
higher than the 12.945 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Despite a 6.6-percent decline in revenues, electronics and
components remained the country's top dollar earner for the month
of May with a 48.3-percent share, amounting to 1.417 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The office said manufactured goods in May posted a 5.1-percent
increase as sales reached 2.615 billion dollars, up from 2.488
billion dollars a year earlier. This major export group accounted
for 89.2 percent of the total receipts.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for 4.6 percent of the total, income from agro-based
products earned 136.28 million dollars in May. Compared with last
year,aggregate revenue for these commodity groups grew by 6.5
percent from 127.95 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the country's largest export market in
May with a share of 28.2 percent. Other top markets for the month
include Japan, the Netherlands, Singapore, China's Hong Kong and
Taiwan and Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
