<HEADLINE> Battle Breaks Out Around Fijian Parliament, 4 Wounded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A battle broke out Tuesday around
Fiji's parliament with at least four people wounded by gunfire,
the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported.
</P>
<P>
The battle followed a mini-mutiny on Fiji's second largest
island of Vanua Levu, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
The battle on the perimeter of the parliamentary compound in
Fiji's capital Suva saw volleys of shots exchanged by the rebels
inside and soldiers stationed around the compound.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted an army spokesman as saying one grenade also
exploded during the fight.
</P>
<P>
The military said four civilians were taken to hospital with
leg wounds.
</P>
<P>
Each side said the other started the battle and the army said
it has been contacted by coup leader George Speight to arrange an
immediate cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, some soldiers at the army base in Vaturekuka, Labasa,
on Fiji's second largest island, mutinied in support of Speight's
Fiji nationalist demands.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman said two soldiers had seized the weapons
held by the garrison in Labasa.
</P>
<P>
The army said there are about 20 soldiers at the base.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation followed the swearing in of Fiji's interim
government headed by Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase, who asked
Speight to set free the hostages he and his men have been holding
in the parliament since last month.
</P>
<P>
"I make a final plea to them. Please release the hostages,"
the new prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet ministers appointed by the military were sworn in
Tuesday morning in Suva. 
</P>
