<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Mori Re-elected Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives re-
elected Yoshiro Mori as prime minister Tuesday afternoon, paving
the way for the formation of a new cabinet later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Mori won the premiership vote with the support of his ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and the party's two junior coalition
partners, the New Komeito party and the New Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
Mori's victory in the lower house means he has been effectively
re-elected Japan's prime minister as the country's constitutional
provisions stipulate that the lower house's election result stands
even if the House of Councilors, the upper house, elects a
different candidate as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Mori was also expected to win approval in the upper house as
the three-party coalition also enjoys a comfortable majority in
the upper chamber. Voting there was scheduled to take place
shortly after the lower house vote.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary votes were held on the first day of a three-
day special Diet (parliament) session following the June 25
general election.
</P>
<P>
The lineup for Mori's new cabinet is expected to be announced
around 6.30 p.m. (0930 GMT). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
