<HEADLINE> Housing Sector to Keep Growing in Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China expects to build houses
ranging between 486 million sq. m to 549 million sq. m in floor
space annually in the first 20 years in the 21st century, with
investment to grow at an annual increase of seven percent.
</P>
<P>
According to Xie Jiajin, director in charge of real estate
development department under the Ministry of Construction, massive
housing construction and increasing housing sales has spurred
China's economic development, which is becoming a major focus of
consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
China has so far maintained a rational and stable real estate
development, and the market with ordinary housing construction as
the pillar has started to pick up.
</P>
<P>
And housing construction continues to expand and sales continue
to grow, which has characterized the present real estate market,
the official added.
</P>
<P>
She said that the country is launching massive housing projects,
building 410 million square meters of floor space in 1999 with
investment totaling 401 billion yuan, up 19.6 percent and 11
percent, respectively, over the 1998 figures.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the implementation of the housing
reform, which means selling houses to citizens instead of
allocating houses to them as material benefits, has played
important roles in developing housing markets.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country has done a lot to stimulate individual
housing spending and launch mortgage-loan services for homebuyers.
And a housing fund-raising system targeted at helping buyers has
been effectively instituted nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Lanzhou City in northwest China
reported slightly polluted air today.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center today, fairly good air was
reported in 26 cities. They are Beijing, Tianjin, Shijiazhuang,
Taiyuan, Hohhot, Shenyang, Changchun, Harbin, Nanjing, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Hefei, Nanchang, Jinan, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha,
Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Shantou, Chongqing, Chengdu, Guiyang, Xi'an,
Xining and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
All the 26 aforementioned cities, except Chongqing and Guiyang,
listed particulates less than 10 microns in size as their major
pollutants, while sulfur dioxide is the major air pollutants in
Chongqing and Guiyang.
</P>
<P>
Dalian, Shanghai, Suzhou, Nantong, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Qingdao,
Yantai, Zhuhai, Zhenjiang, Nanning, Haikou, Kunming, Lhasa and
Yinchuan reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes below 50),
level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 51 to 100)
, level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes ranging from
101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes ranging from 201
to 300) and level-five or hazardous (pollution indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
