<HEADLINE> India's Software Exports Up 57 Percent in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- India's software exports rose by
57 percent to 171.5 billion rupees (4 billion U.S. dollars) in the
1999-2000 fiscal year from 109.4 billion rupees (2.65 billion
dollars) in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey published by the National Association of
Software and Service Companies (Nasscom) Tuesday, the country's
software and services industry grossed a total revenue of 243.5
billion rupees (5.7 billion dollars) in 1999-2000, up 53 percent
from 158.9 billion rupees (3.9 billion dollars) for the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
India's fiscal year ends on March 31.
</P>
<P>
The United States continued to be the major market for Indian
software and services with a share of 62 percent while Europe
accounted for 23.5 percent in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The Nasscom is projecting that software exports will continue
to grow and will reach 6.3 billion dollars in 2000-2001. 
</P>
