<HEADLINE> SAARC Starts Agriculture, Rural Development Meeting in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the SAARC
Technical Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development kicked
off here Tuesday with the participation of all the seven member
countries of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, SAARC Secretary-General Nihal
Rodrigo described the meeting as of great significance because it
is the first SAARC-level meeting after the postponement of the
SAARC summit slated for November last year.
</P>
<P>
"This meeting set what I am certain is a healthy precedent for
other SAARC technical committees to follow," said Rodrigo.
</P>
<P>
The significance of the meeting also lies in the fact that all
the seven SAARC member countries -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal, the
Maldives, Pakistan, India and Sri Lanka -- are represented,
Rodrigo said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting will be discussing issues of the
development of the agricultural and rural sectors, which is the
core of development in South Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
This is because about 80 percent of the people live in rural
areas in South Asia and agriculture accounts for over 30 percent
of the GDP in the region, Rodrigo added.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking on the occasion, Baldeo Majgainya, Nepal's
minister of state for agriculture and cooperatives, said that as
the meeting is the first of a technical committee of the
restructured SAARC Integrated Program of Action (IPA), it will "
define the strategies for promotion of cooperation under the IPA."
</P>
<P>
"The two-day deliberations will result in recommendations
toward the fulfillment of the fundamental goals of poverty
alleviation in the region," said Majgainya.
</P>
<P>
About 100 delegates from the seven SAARC countries and some U.N.
agencies are participating in the meeting co-organized by the
SAARC Secretariat and the Nepali government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
