<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Launch 5-Year Project for Food Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Agricultural
Extension (DAE will launch a five-year project in October this
year to enhance the level of food security and nutrition, The
Bangladesh Observer newspaper reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Funded by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), the
project "Integrated Horticulture and Nutrition Development" is
designed to improve the nutritional status of the population
through creating an environment in which households will have
sufficient access to fruits and vegetables at affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
Also aiming at improving the associated services such as
marketing, processing credit and post-harvest loss prevention, the
project will be implemented in areas around 15 Horticulture
Development Training Centers in different districts.
</P>
<P>
It will provide training to 31,400 beneficiaries who will be
small, marginal and landless farmers with a special focus on women.
Rural women, specially homestead gardeners, are the main target
beneficiaries of this project.
</P>
<P>
The project to be assisted by a technical advisory group of the
Food and Agricultural Organization of the United Nations will be
nationally executed by the Department of Agricultural Extension
under the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The total duration of the project is five years from October,
2000, with a total assistance of 5.346 million U.S. dollars
provided by the UNDP.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that such efforts will help promote the
production and productivity, and increase incomes to the small and
marginal farming communities in a sustainable manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
