<HEADLINE> Thailand to Consider Extradition of Lao Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will consider request from
Laos to extradite 27 Lao rebels who fled into the country and were
detained by the Thai authorities Monday, the government said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand will consider the extradition based on the 1929
Extradition Treaty, because the two countries have yet to ratify
an extradition treaty they signed last year," Thai foreign
ministry spokesman Don Pramudwinai said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lao ambassador to Thailand Hiem Phommachamh said
that Lao officials are holding talks with their Thai counterparts
to seek the return of those rebels.
</P>
<P>
The 27 will be charged by the Thai authorities with illegal
entry, according to Don.
</P>
<P>
The 27 were among the over 100 Lao rebels who on Monday seized
a Lao customs checkpoint and clashed with the Lao government
troops, leading to five dead and several injured.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Thai prime minister Chuan Leekpai reaffirmed
his government would not allow any armed groups to use Thailand
for activities against the Lao government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
