<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's NPLs Drop for 12th Consecutive Month in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's non-performing loans (
NPLs)fell for the twelfth consecutive month in May, to about 1.9
trillion baht (49.3 billion U.S. dollars), or 35.63 percent of the
total loans of the country, according to a report released by the
Bank of Thailand (BOT Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of NPLs to total loans fell 0.84 percent from 36.47
percent in April, after peaking at 47.7 percent in May last year,
as more companies renegotiated their debt with lenders, it stated.
</P>
<P>
"The declining NPLs is a positive sign of the country's
financial standing, particularly when it continues uniformly in
twelve consecutive months," BOT Director of Banking Analysis
Department Samart Buranawathanachoke was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The trend is satisfactory, but the falling pace is rather slow,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
BOT, the central bank, will issue directives to speed up debt
restructuring processes after it concludes the final review soon,
he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The central bank expects the bad loan ratio to fall below 10
percent by the end of this year as banks speed up debt
restructuring and complete the transfer of delinquent loans to new
asset management units, the official remarked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
