<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Develet Bahceli said on
Monday that the eighth five-year development plan "is vital" for
Turkey to display its economic growth potential in the coming
years, Turkey's Anatolia news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Bahceli said at a press briefing that the plan, which was
approved by the parliament last week, aims to reach an average 7
percent economic growth over 2001 and 2003. (Turkey-Development)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Despite an optimistic outlook for the medium
term, U.N. economists warn that the world economy is vulnerable to
a number of potential threats.
</P>
<P>
Among others, a sharp swing in major exchange rates is possible,
when trade imbalances of the major countries become a matter of
concern in financial markets, they said in the World Economic and
Social Survey 2000, released in New York Monday. (UN-World
Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The world economy is projected to grow 3.5
percent in 2000, surpassing the growth rates of 1.9 percent and 2.
7 percent for 1998 and 1999, and the post-Asian-crisis rebound has
a good change of continuing for some years to come, according to a
U.N. report released in New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
The upswing is subject to various short-term threats and growth
in most of the poorest countries remains inadequate to meeting
world poverty-fighting goals, said the U.N. World Economic and
Social Survey 2000. (UN-World Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)'s currency, dirham,
pegged to the U.S. dollar, is expected to remain stable over the
next two years due to expected higher oil revenues and an upturn
in foreign reserves and assets, economists said.
</P>
<P>
The strength of the dollar will ensure the strength of the
dirham against other main currencies, said the Economist
Intelligence Unit (EIU), an information provider for companies
establishing and managing operations across national borders, in
its latest report on UAE released on Monday. (UAE-Currency)
</P>
<P>
