<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Revises Censorship Laws After Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
revised press censorship laws effective from the first of this
month following a Supreme Court ruling, the state radio said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The radio said President Chandrika Kumaratunga had issued an
extraordinary gazette notification proscribing reporting affecting
the morale of soldiers and reporting on proposed military
operations and purchases.
</P>
<P>
The new censorship laws will prohibit reporting which incites
public unrest and military coup.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga's notification followed recommendations
by a committee comprising of Ministers G.L. Peiris and Mangala
Samaraweera and Attorney General K.C. Kamalasabayson.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Supreme Court ruled that the blanket censorship
imposed on May 3 when separatist Tamil Tiger rebels stepped up
attacks in the northern Jaffna peninsula was illegal as the censor
was not properly appointed.
</P>
<P>
However, officials said the shortcomings pointed out by the
Supreme Court had been corrected in President Kumaratunga's
notification.
</P>
<P>
The notification said Director of Information Ariya Rubasinghe
was re-appointed as the Competent Authority. He will impose
restraining orders against those who are found guilty in violating
the Emergency Regulations.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the government asked foreign correspondents here
not to submit their reports to the censor as the regulations were
being eased for the international press.
</P>
<P>
The government used the censorship to close down three
newspapers. However, the Supreme Court ordered the reopening of
two on Friday after holding that the censorship was illegal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
