<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Prices Rise Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite OPEC's announcement in June
to increase crude oil production by 708,000 barrels a day from
July 1, crude prices have again risen, the oil cartel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) in Vienna said its oil prices rose further last
week, to an average 29.78 U.S. dollars per barrel, from 28.89
dollars the week before.
</P>
<P>
With last week's rise, the average price for the month of June
was 29.11 dollars per barrel, it said. In May the average was 26.
94 dollars.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's official target price is 25 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The oil cartel boosted its output on March 29 in an effort to
keep the price down.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC news agency said Benchmark Brent Crude for August
delivery was trading 48 cents higher at 31.05 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
In New York, light sweet crude for August delivery slipped 22
cents on Friday to close at 32.50 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia intends to put 500,000 barrels of oil on the
market every day starting immediately to try to get soaring prices
down to 25 U.S. dollars a barrel, an official from an OPEC
delegation disclosed Monday.
</P>
<P>
But Leo Drollas, chief economist of the London-based Center for
Global Energy Studies said, "It sounds too desperate for the
Saudis. They wouldn't want to be seen to act ... without some of
the others coming along with them."
</P>
<P>
OPEC members are Saudi Arabia, Iran, the United Arab Emirates,
Kuwait, Qatar, Nigeria, Libya, Algeria, Venezuela and Indonesia.
Iraq is also a member but has not participated in recent OPEC
production pacts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record High Temperatures Hit Poland in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Record high temperatures hit Poland
in June this year, making drought worse in many parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Temperature reached 36.9 degrees Celsius in Kolo on June 22,
the highest for the month of June since 1951, according to the
Polish Research Institute on Meteorology and Water Conservancy.
</P>
<P>
Other cities, such as Thorn and Cracow, also experienced record
high temperatures during the month.
</P>
<P>
Warsaw's average temperature in June arrived at 17.6 degree
Celsius, one degree higher than the June average.
</P>
<P>
In April, the average temperature in the capital city reached
14.4 degree Celsius, 4.4 degrees higher than that of the April
average.
</P>
<P>
Drought in the country grew more serious in June, with many
areas having only between 30 percent and 80 percent of the
rainfall in normal years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
