<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stiffer Anti-faking Measures Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Rampant counterfeit products are a
serious menace to the survival of enterprises and the Chinese
government should deal with the problem by enforcing legal
structure, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of counterfeit products in China has exceeded
that of smuggled goods, the English-language newspaper quoted a
senior government policy consultant as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoji, director-general of the Foreign Economy Relations
Department of the Development Research Center under the State
Council, said in an investigation report that the anti-
counterfeiting measures should be as powerful as the anti-
smuggling measures that the government introduced last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that forceful anti-counterfeiting measures will produce
greater economic benefits than anti-smuggling measure because they
will help prevent the evasion of a great many taxes, restore
market order and improve the investment environment.
</P>
<P>
China stepped up its anti-smuggling campaign last year and
dramatically increased customs taxes and enterprises profits.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang's report based on a nation-wide survey of
420 Chinese and foreign companies, counterfeiting is still a
serious problem that is hindering China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
"The government should realize that forceful anti-
counterfeiting measures are necessary for the success of the
economic reforms," Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
