<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Students Seeking Degrees in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 44,711 foreign students
from 164 countries sought degrees in diverse subjects in China
last year, some 1,700 more than 1998.
</P>
<P>
Most of the students are from Asia, followed by Europe, America,
Africa and Oceania, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the biggest source of foreign students, followed by
the Republic of Korea, the United States, Indonesia and Germany,
said sources from the Department of International Cooperation and
Exchange under the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
Last year, master's and doctoral degrees began replacing lower
degrees as the targets of foreign students. Some 869 students
studied for doctoral degrees last year, up 27 percent from the
previous year. Master's degree students numbered 2,000, up 14
percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted department official Hu Zhiping as saying
that, foreign students studied subjects ranging from the arts,
sciences, medicine, agronomy and sports, compared with traditional
choices, such as language and culture.
</P>
<P>
More than 80,000 foreign students enjoyed Chinese government
scholarships, while the other 270,000 studied at their own
expenses, the ministry's statistics showed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
