<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Bank Owners to Surrender Assets to Repay Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The owners of 25 banks closed down
by the government last year signed an agreement with the
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) to surrender assets to
repay some 1.22 billion U.S. dollars in debts to the government.
</P>
<P>
"The shareholders of 25 closed banks have signed the terms and
conditions of the shareholder settlement program with IBRA," IBRA
deputy chairman Arwin Rasyid was quoted by the Jakarta Post
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The owners of the banks owed the government approximately 10.5
trillion rupiah (1.22 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Arwin said that the owners were expected to complete the entire
legal process of the asset transfer in September at the latest.
</P>
<P>
The 25 banks are part of the 38 banks closed down by the
government in 1999 due to financial distress, insolvency or
violations of the legal lending limit and other banking
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The government injected massive liquidity support between 1998
and 1999 to bail out the banking industry when confidence in the
industry plunged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
