<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF lifts Ottey Drugs Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Amateur Athletic
Federation (IAAF) announced late Monday that the ban imposed on
Jamaican sprint star Merlene Ottey for failing a drugs test has
been lifted.
</P>
<P>
In a statement athletics' governing body explained that its
arbitration panel had "decided that there were not the grounds to
maintain the suspension of Merlene Ottey from competition."
</P>
<P>
Ottey, the 200m world champion in 1997, tested positive for
nandrolone on July 5 last year in Switzerland,just a few days
before the World Athletics Championships started in Seville.
</P>
<P>
However the IAAF said: "The arbitration panel considered that
the testing laboratory had not taken into sufficient account
factors regarding the specific gravity of the sample, which as a
result did not exceed the IOC (International Olympic Committee)
recommended reporting threshold."
</P>
<P>
The panel was made up of chairman Christoph Vedder of Germany,
South African Monty Hacker and James Michael Murphy of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Ottey's case had been considered at a hearing at IAAF
headquarters in Monaco between June 16-17.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old, known as the 'Lion Queen', had always denied
the charge and had been cleared by the Jamaican national athletics
federation.
</P>
<P>
Ottey had pulled out of the world championships in Spain last
August in a blaze of publicity after her second test from the
Lucerne meeting had been returned positive.
</P>
<P>
She insisted at the time that there had been a "terrible
mistake" and ovwed to clear her name. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
