<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Output of Summer Grain Drops in Northern Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The output of summer grain has
dropped by 500 million kilograms this year compared with last year
in north China's Hebei province, one of China's major granaries.
</P>
<P>
Government officials attributed it to the downsizing of wheat
fields. Many villagers have used their farmland to produce
vegetables and fruits, resulting in a decrease of 490,000 hectares
of wheat plowland.
</P>
<P>
Heavy drought has also affected the production, according to
sources. A total of 1.2 million hectares of grain have suffered
the drought that is still hovering over the entire north China.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 million people are mobilized every day to fight against
the drought across the country, reports say.
</P>
<P>
However, the output of high quality wheat is expected to rise,
sources claim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
