<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Ready to Attend Arab Summit: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Saudi Foreign Minister Saud
Al-Faisal asserted here Tuesday that his country is ready to attend
an Arab summit once the Arab League decides its time and venue.
</P>
<P>
Al-Faisal made the pledge at a joint press conference with his
Yemeni counterpart Abdul Qader Ba-Jammal after exchanging copies of
a border agreement between Saudi Arabia and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The accord has removed all obstacles to the development of
bilateral ties and opened the door wide for the Saudi-Yemeni
cooperation, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
It also created an atmosphere of optimism in the Arab world,
said the minister, expressing his country's desire to play a role
in settling any border dispute in the Persian Gulf area.
</P>
<P>
On the Yemeni bid to join the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC),
the Saudi foreign minister said that there were no reservations
among the Arab Gulf countries on Yemen's GCC membership.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, established in 1981, is a regional political and
economic alliance grouping Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Bahrain,
Qatar and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi-Yemeni ties are deeply rooted and are not restricted
to the existing GCC frameworks, he pointed out. The bilateral ties
are older than the GCC, he added.
</P>
<P>
Al-Faisal welcomed the Yemeni laborers to his country, noting
that there were no restrictions on their presence in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Ba-Jammal said the border agreement would be put
into force after its copies were exchanged. The accord ushered in a
new era in the bilateral ties, featuring partnership rather than
neighborliness, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries charged a number of institutions to demarcate
the bilateral borders and work out relevant security arrangements,
Ba-Jammal noted. The chiefs of general staff of the two countries
will take charge of the military affairs on the borders.
</P>
<P>
Under the document, the armed forces of the two countries will
pull out by 20 kilometers far from the border lines defined in the
border accord. The deal defined land, air and maritime borders
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh said during his meeting with
Al-Faisal that the deal was a turning point in the bilateral ties
and would establish the basis for peace, security and stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Yemen, with a 2,500-kilometer common border,
had been locked in a territorial dispute, which in 1998 flared up
into a border conflict.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed the border accord in the western
Saudi city of Jeddah last month during a two-day visit to Saudi
Arabia by Yemeni President Saleh.
</P>
<P>
Prince al-Faisal left here Tuesday evening after a one-day
official visit to Yemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
