<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Middle East News Summary at 2100GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said Tuesday
morning that without Israelis consent, the Palestinians will not
succeed in unilaterally declaring an independent state in
September.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio, Beilin added that even if Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat makes a unilateral announcement, an
independent Palestinian state will not be really established
without Israel's agreement.
</P>
<P>
Without Israel's recognition, he said, the Palestinian state
will exist only on paper, even if "the whole world recognizes the
new-born state." (Israel-Palestinian-Statehood)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A majority of the Palestinians believe Israel and
the Palestinians can not reach a peace agreement by September as
stipulated in the Sharm el Sheikh interim deal, a poll result
released here Tuesday indicated.
</P>
<P>
Some 59.8 percent of the Palestinians said the two sides can not
strike a final peace deal by that time while only 17.8 percent
believe they can meet the target, showed the poll, conducted by
Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC) on June 23 among 1,
200 Palestinians from the West Bank, Gaza Strip and Jerusalem.
(Israel-Palestinian-Poll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The guerrillas group Hezbollah of Lebanon said here on
Tuesday it will continue its struggle against Israel until the
Jewish state returns all occupied Lebanese lands.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Seyed Hassan Nasrallah, secretary
general of Hezbollah, upon his arrival here for the first visit to
Iran after the withdrawal of Israeli forces from South Lebanon.
(Iran-Hezbollah)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein stressed on Tuesday
that peace remains a strategic option for Jordan, and the kingdom
will continue its efforts to promote the Arab-Israeli peace process
in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a written interview with Xinhua, King Abdullah said currently
the peace process is at a delicate stage, and Jordan has been and
will be in persistent touches with parties concerned to revive and
push forward peace talks on all fronts, including the Palestinian
and Syrian tracks. (Jordan-King-Interview) 
</P>
</TEXT>
