<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Announces Offensive to Strengthen OPEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
said Tuesday that an offensive to strengthen OPEC has been started,
which includes telephone contacts with his ten counterparts of the
bloc and a tour through the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Chavez, whose country presides Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), said he got in contact Tuesday with
Algeria's President and Saudi Arabia's King before "pressures" so
that producing countries increase crude extraction and lower price
of the barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan leader said that he put forward to both
dignitaries the need to "keep on strengthening OPEC".
</P>
<P>
Venezuela expressed Monday its ignorance regarding
announcement of Saudi Arabia, greatest producer and exporter of
oil , to increase production by 500,000 barrels daily if crude
prices remain high, as the press reports.
</P>
<P>
Chavez said that this Tuesday a Venezuelan mission made up by
Vice Foreign Minister Jorge Valero and Minister of Energy, and
OPEC President Ali Rodriguez is leaving for all cartel countries.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of this tour is to prepare the journey Venezuela's
leader will carry out to "all" OPEC member countries after July 30,
when the country will celebrate elections to legitimize its
institutions in the framework of a new Carta Magna.
</P>
<P>
He said that his county's working on organizing 3rd OPEC Summit,
which will take place in Caracas between September 28 and 30, year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Chavez also let know he talked Monday with his counterpart from
Nigeria, and with Mexico's President-elect Vicente Fox. Mexico is
not an OPEC member, but has played a determining part in defense
of oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
