<DOCNO> XIE20000704.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Hit by Oil and Telecoms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) - Europe's major stock markets ended
lower Tuesday, as weak oil stocks dragged London market lower.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index slipped 53.4 points, or 0.8 percent to
6415.8, a day after rising 2.5 percent in its largest one-day
point gain this year.
</P>
<P>
Shares of BP Amoco, second only to Vodafone AirTouch among the
most heavily weighted shares in the FTSE 100, fell 2.8 percent.
Shell Transport and Trading shed 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The oil sector was under pressure after Saudi Arabia announced
plans to boost oil production to try to bring prices down. Brent
crude oil fell 1.04 US dollars to 30.06 per barrel in London.
</P>
<P>
However, Brewer Scottish &AMP; Newcastle was the biggest decliner
on the FTSE 100, losing 7.4 percent after its annual earnings fell
a larger-than-expected 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The German DAX index closed slightly down in thin trade with
index heavy-weights remaining weak. The index ended down 0.21
percent or 14.60 points at 6944.36.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 index in Paris closed down 13.7 points, or 0.2
percent, at 6494.77. French technology stocks were mixed but
France Telecom fell 4.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
