<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires Burn on Western Slope in U.S. Colorado State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The reports quoted a local official as saying that the larger
blaze started Monday in the Dinosaur National Monument in remote
northwestern Colorado, and was burning on nearly 3,400 hectares
about 10 kilometers from the Utah border.
</P>
<P>
The blaze was burning mostly on federal land, and no structures
were immediately threatened.
</P>
<P>
Farther south, firefighters feared dry conditions and strong
winds would cause a blaze burning on 800 hectares about 50
kilometers southwest of Grand Junction to spread.
</P>
<P>
In southwestern Wyoming, two wildfires believed to have been
started by lighting had burned about 650 hectares of shrubs and
grass on public and private land over two days, according to the
reports.
</P>
<P>
The wildfires came less than a month after two blazes burned
about 8,500 hectares on the more densely populated eastern side of
the Continental Divide, destroying dozens of homes and other
structures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
