<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican President-elect To Look for Alliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Winner of last Sunday's
presidential election in Mexico, Vicente Fox, said Tuesday he'll
look for alliances with diverse internal political forces for a
peaceful transition.
</P>
<P>
Fox, from opposing Alliance for Change, will take office on
December 1 as first president coming from an opposition putting
end to 71 years of presidential monopoly of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
No political party has absolute majority in Congress, wherefore
alliances will be necessary, said Fox at a meeting with the
foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
At the same occasion, Fox said he would visit extensively in
the next few months, to seek improved ties with Mexico's partners
and to promote investments.
</P>
<P>
He is planning to visit the United States, Canada and several
European and Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
Fox expressed hope to strengthen the North American Free Trade
(NAFTA) agreement between Canada and the United States in order to
create a market similar to the European Common Market.
</P>
<P>
The 58-year old former rancher and Coca Cola regional
executive got 43 percent of the votes on Sunday's presidential
election, while Fransico Labastida, the candidate of the ruling
party, won 36 percent and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist candidate,
won 17 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
